animal.description:
Here is Isla!

Isla and her sisters, Cordelia and Lana, are about 4-5 months old and they are very special pups.  They spent the first 3 months of their lives outside under their owners porch. Luckly, someone called animal control and they were seized. The siblings were taken to an over populated shelter and the shelter called us to help.  FHDR transported the pups to NJ to live in foster homes.  They are very happy to be in a foster home where they are getting healthy food & treats, soft beds and lots of love. Something they never experienced before.  The pups are very shy but so very sweet and they are learning to trust people. 

Isla foster mom says….”Isla is gorgeous.  She has beautiful haze eyes and a beautiful brown coat.  Isla was very shy when she arrived at our house but she is making a lot of progress. She will now will come over to us and she will give us puppy kisses.  Isla spends her days playing with all sorts of toys (ring toys, rope toys, sneaky toys, stuffed toys and kong) and she loves her balls (small, large squishy ones).  Isla will toss her toys up in the air and then chases after them. She will also play fetch with her the balls and return them.  Isla will follow us around and she likes relaxing on her doggie bed or sitting outside in the sun. She is very silly puppy who runs around the house when she has the zoomies and getting into stuff. LOL!  Isla rolls over for belly rubs all the time.  And, she does this cute thing where she slides from a sit position to a laying position. LOL!  Isla sleeps through the night without having accidents and she is doing really good with house training. She already know the comands sit, paw, down, come and no. She is food motivated and very obedient for a puppy.  Isla is a vocal puppy, she has a little whine that sounds like a bird chirping. She is very cute and the sounds are adorble!!"

Isla needs a home that has the patience to make her feel comfortable and that can spend time teaching her that they are safe.  (No children under 15 years old.) are sure if you adopt her, she will be devoted, loving companion.  She just need the right person to call their own. Isla is just a Love!

If you have a furever home for this pet, please e-mail Furever Home Dog Rescue at FureverHomeDogRescue@gmail.com and request an adoption application. 

The breed and age of this pet is listed as is our best guess.  We have no background info on who the mom and dad are.

Please note we do not adopt puppies/dogs to homes where they will be left alone all day. 

We do not have a shelter facility you can visit.  Our volunteers foster the dogs and pups in their homes once they have been vetted and transported here to NJ.

Please read our homepage www.fhdr.petfinder.com to read how the adoption process works. And, please visit Furever Home Dog Rescue's homepage www.FureverHomeDogRescue.com to see some of our many reviews.  Thank you!

Cordelia and her sisters, Lana and Isla, are about 4-5 months old and they are very special pups.  They spent the first 3 months of their lives outside under their owners porch. animal.description: Beautiful, big boy Atlas is just over 1yrs old and currently weighs 95lbs.  He is a skinny boy and needs to fill out so we expect him to exceed 100lbs when fully grown.  He is a very friendly, social boy that will be a wonderful family dog.  He loves long walks, hiking trips and playing in the yard so an active family is required.  He is a typical shepherd so can be somewhat protective of his family when other dogs visit in the home so he must be the only dog.  When outdoors and away from his home, he does love to play with other large dogs.  He has great house manners and has some basic obedience but additional training will help him continue to be a well balanced pup.  Because he is such a large boy, kids must be over 14yrs old and he MUST have a large breed, German Shepherd experienced home.  He must also have a 6ft securely fenced yard... the bigger the better! If you are interested in meeting Atlas please email info@k9rr.org and include your phone number.

animal.description:
Good with male submissive dogs, no cats or young children. House-trained.
HW-

Phoenix showed up at the rural home of a Good Samaritan, who took pity on this sweet girl! She had wounds that covered her legs, shoulders and underbody. The Good Samaritan took her to the veterinarian, where she was vaccinated and given medication for infection of her wounds. After a professional assessment, it is believed that Phoenix was the victim of a horrible dog attack or possibly used as bait dog. The scarring on her legs and belly is consistent with a scenario where she was attempting to submit, but was attacked unmercifully anyway. Phoenix is an amazing girl, because she is so loving in spite of her past and wants only to please her humans. She loves interacting with people. Phoenix has truly risen from her ashes and is looking for a forever home where she will be loved for who she is, with or without the scars.
Please note: We only accept adoption applications through our website or in person (Facebook and Petfinder inquiries are not considered applications).

animal.description:
Hello!

My name is Benji. I am a male Terrier who is about a year old and 40 pounds.

Where do I start... I was found as a stray by some doggy catcher and they brought me to a dark and scary shelter. They said I was not friendly and couldn't walk. Thankfully that didn't stop Houston Animal Rescue Team from saving me.

As it turns out, I was abused by humans and both my back legs have sever injuries. Surgery is possible but will cause more bad than good. So, with lots of love and care, I started to walk and to open up. I am now one of the sweetest pup out there. I love to give kisses and cuddles. I walk funny, my face has a cute twist but I am one kind of a dog. I am potty trained and super friendly with other dogs.

My ideal family would have a yard and would be mellow and like to watch TV with me.

To meet me, please apply on https://www.hartrescue.com/adoption-foster-application-formTo meet me, please fill out an adoption application on https://www.hartrescue.com/adoption-process

If you're interested in adopting, please send us a completed dog adoption application back to us digitally:

http://jenniferspetrescue.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/CanineAdoption.pdf

We go in the order in which we received completed (and approved) adoption applications and not by Petfinder inquiries.  Once your application has been approved, then we will answer any questions you may have.  Also you must be LOCAL to Dallas, GA; within an hour or so to adopt from us.  We apologize in advance, but we just don’t have the resources to get back to every single person that inquires to adopt from us during COVID-19, but know that we do try.  You’ll hear from us ASAP if you are picked to adopt!

P.S.	Petsmart adoptions are a thing of the past for now, so no we will not be there this weekend.  All adoptions are done by appt. only now in Dallas, GA and if you see this animal listed on Petfinder, then YES he or she is still available for adoption.

animal.description:
Brodi is a 3-year-old Saint Bernard. He is 125 pounds of sheer love. Brodi loves to give full-body hugs and once you're in his arms, he likes to squeeze to let you know how much he loves you. True to the breed, he loves all people big and small. So why would this perfect love end up on rescue? Life sometimes has different plans than you expect and his family came upon hard times. So they asked Angels to help find a better situation for Brodi and his sister (Didi).

Brodi'e perfect home will have a fenced yard. This big boy is just too big for an apartment, and have larger kids just because of his size. Brodi also has the classic case of "I know my size and can use it to my advantage"- as sweet as he is, he is also stubborn. Brodi does what Brodi wants. So his best family will continue to work with him and will understand if he doesn't want to get a bath, you just may not be able to give him one or get really creative. He would do well with a fenced yard, although not extremely active, he does need to stretch those long legs! As with any giant breed, any new family will also have to understand having a dog of this size, everything costs double (prevents, medical care ).

Since Brodi is still new to his foster family, they will be doing some additional dog evaluations (so far so good). For example, leash evaluations and just spending time with him, getting to know him better to best understand his best future home. Stay tuned for updates. We have found that a lot of dogs are intimated by his size, so we will need to evaluate each potential home with dogs based on how comfortable they are sharing it with the jolly green giant!

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online. http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

animal.description:
Nelly arrived at NCCR on 1/8/21, surrendered due to  separation anxiety.  Her family wasn't able to be home as much as Nelly needed them to be.  She had originally been adopted from NCCR in 2019 after being pulled from an overcrowded shelter. She is a spayed female, thought to be a Labrador Retriever mix, approximately 2 ½ - 3 years old. Nelly had cherry eye, which was repaired prior to her arrival. Nelly is very friendly toward people, including children, and most other dogs. She is house trained. Nelly could use some obedience training to improve her manners, as in her excitement to meet people, she does sometimes jumps up.  Nelly cannot be safely crated, as she panics and may hurt herself trying to escape the crate. She does not like to be alone  but that might possibly be helped by having a doggie companion to spend her alone time with.  She gets along great with dogs at the Rescue and loves their playtime together.  We believe the right family for her will have another dog, not be gone long hours and have the patience to work with her anxieties.  She's really a very sweet and lovable girl who will flourish in the right situation.  

Nelly is spayed, vaccinated (including bordetella) and microchipped. Her adoption fee is $215.00. (cash or check only, we are unable to accept credit cards)

Nelly is sponsored by Robert Tipton, Sandra Pavlock, Jill Reese, Elaine Tschari and Ron and Brenda Johnson, Lucinda Gelsmino, Randy and Debby Ruhland and Will and Cindy Hepfer in memory of Skye and Rosa McDonald. Thank you everyone!

If you think you might be interested in adopting, your first step should be to complete an adoption application. APPLICATION to ADOPT: Copy and paste this link in your browser to view and complete the application https://forms.gle/NghtT4WTNiaZu7Cg9. You can also select the link, right click and choose open in a new window.

We do adopt out of state, however we do not transport or ship dogs.  Potential adopter must be able and willing to travel to the Rescue to meet the dog they are interested in.  

*PLEASE double check all of the phone numbers that you provide as if they are incorrect, we will be unable to process your application.  Please also let your references know that someone from NCCR will be calling them. Most adoption team members call from their personal phone so advise your references that there may be an unknown number or a private number calling them.  

NYS Registration #RR028.

animal.description:
Maggie II
5 Years Old
90 lbs
American Bulldog
Natural Tail
House & Crate Trained
Basic Obedience Skills
Fostered in Snohomish, WA

Hi, it's me, Maggie! I'm a body positive influencer waiting to find my forever home. Not to toot my own horn, but everyone that meets me says I'm very beautiful. My hobbies include: playing with stuffed animals, getting belly rubs and sleeping in. I love playing with toys and can occupy myself for quite a bit of time. I'm ok with other dogs, but would prefer that they leave me alone to play with my toys by myself. My foster fur siblings keep calling me an attention hog, whatever that means. I also like going for walks, will you take me? I can pull a bit, but foster mom says that I get into the rhythm eventually. I am on the larger side, and do require my people to be confident in their ability to handle me at times.

My new year's resolution is to eat healthier and to get more exercise. Is that your resolution too? Maybe we can work on it together?

Maggie's foster mom here: Maggie is sweet, playful and most of all loving. Maggie is very attached to her people and will follow you wherever you go. Maggie knows basic obedience and is potty trained. Maggie is so sweet; she is sure to win you over. Her striking good looks help too. It has been so easy having her in our home, she is very settled and adapted easily to our routine. Seriously though, how can you resist her underbite?! Does she sound like the girl for you? Apply today!

animal.description:
***REQUIRES A FENCED IN YARD***

***FOSTERED IN PANAMA CITY AREA***

Leta is a 7 month old great dane who is gentle natured and timid, but very sweet, and great with kids, dogs big and small. She came to us after living her first six months of life outside during the day and in an outdoor shed at night.

She is currently living in foster care with other dogs and kids and she is super affectionate and playful. She's learning potty training and crate training for the first time now.

Despite her innocent looks, this little girl has discovered that she can dig under the fence to get to the neighbors chickens... So a fenced in yard is definitely required for her and she should not be left alone unattended outside because she is a digger!

Although she has not been around cats with us, she previously lived with them around and we don't see her being aggressive to one. 

Leta is now spayed and fully vetted and chipped. Her adoption fee is $400. 

To apply to adopt Leta please go to www.nwflgdr.com/adopt.

ATTENTION: NWFLGDR DOES NOT TRANSPORT. If you are applying from out of area or out of state, understand that if your application gets approved, you will be expected to pick up the dane in the location that he/she is being fostered. In addition, if the adoption does not work out, it is your responsibility to bring the dane safely back to us.

animal.description:
Foster or adopter needed! Lady is so stressed in the shelter and needs a break. Maybe you could foster her? Or even offer her a forever home!

Lady is such a sweet, loving girl. She's about four years old and adores people. She gets positively wiggly and happy when she sees you. (Lady is extra excited to see you if you have a little snack to share.) She's good in the car and enjoys a nice nap, too. 

Lady would love a foster or forever home without other dogs. She has ignored cats but does take a very intense interest in squirrels. 

Please call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 for more info on how to meet Lady. She's hanging out in Lawrence, KS, but transport is available to the right foster or forever home! 
 

INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS PET? Fill out an Adoption Application now! Appointments can also be made to meet a pet by calling us at 913-671-PETS (913-671-7387).  

ADOPTION INFORMATION:
Prior to adoption, our animals are: 
**Tested for diseases 
**Vaccinated 
**Spayed/neutered 
**Microchipped 

NO COST adoptions with an encouraged donation are accepted. 

The Pet Connection also offers adopters a FREE veterinary examination and a medical care support plan for 60 days after adoption, as well as lifetime behavioral training, safe sanctuary for pets returned in emergency situations, extensive assistance with lost and found pets, and other expert pet services in a variety of areas, including pet selection, behavioral issues, general training, nutrition, and transition to adoptive homes.

Please visit our website at www.thepetconnection.org for more information about The Pet Connection and for a full listing of our available pets, 

Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 if you can foster, adopt, or sponsor a special needs dog or cat! 

The Pet Connection is a membership organization operating a no-kill adoption center in Shawnee, Kansas.

animal.description: Here is what my foster mom has to say about me: Two year old Taz (also known as Razzmataz, we have already nicknamed her) was hit by a car in November 2019 and surrendered to Pacc shortly after. Her right hind leg was amputated and is fully healed from her injuries and adapted to the tripod life- she gets around like she has 6 legs! Her positive energy and happy-go-lucky personality shine brighter than the Tucson summer sun. The words cuddle bug, teddy bear, snuggle bunny, sweetie pie, can't describe just how incredibly sweet she is. I have fostered many dogs over the years and she is truly special and one of a kind. Taz is potty trained- not one accident since she's been with us! She loves to play with other dogs, however can be pushy during play, therefore an equally playful dog is recommended. She would thrive as an only dog in the home, which I believe to be best. Not sure if she would be ok around cats, but she is calm around my chickens. Taz loves and craves human attention. She doesn't show signs of separation anxiety at this point. Does ok in a kennel, but we haven't had a need to use it much. She loves walks. She gets so excited that she has a tendency to pull. Having only 3 legs doesn't slow this girl down, so she'll need a little leash training. Taz responds to her name and comes when called. She knows sit and we are working on down. Her eye contact is on point and she is eager to please. She likes toys and fetch and plays very gentle with people, young and old. She takes treats so gentle it's as if she doesn't have teeth! She is respectful of boundries like the kitchen table, couch, bed, however we enjoy her loving company so she is allowed to join us in these areas. Car rides are a treat and she does well during the short drives we've taken so far. She is the perfect mix of playful and chill. I think she would make a wonderful therapy dog and is a perfect family dog- a diamond in the rough.

animal.description: As is the case for most everyone, 2020 was a bit rough on Iroh. This big, beautiful boy came to PACC in a pretty neglected state, needing major surgery and a lot of TLC. He went through a lot both before coming to PACC, and while recovering from surgeries in the shelter environment. Despite everything he's been through, Iroh has kept a positive attitude- everyone who's met him says he's the sweetest, friendliest boy ever! Iroh recently returned from a stay in his foster home- here is what his foster had to say about this big teddy bear: - Iroh is very easy to walk and well behaved in the home. - He is housebroken - He slept in the living room on a dog bed and doesn't tend to jump up on furniture. - He enjoys chewing on rawhide bones and likes ropes for tug of war. - He is very cuddly, friendly, and definitely a couch potato who snoozes the day away. - He LOVES belly rubs and enjoys rides in the car (he needs a little boost to get in). - He dislikes stairs and would likely do best in a single level home. Iroh is an affectionate, easygoing, sweetheart of a guy who is a definite shelter favorite. He would likely do best as an only pet, but he's so loving that he'll be enough! Ask to meet him today!

animal.description: Ponyo is a sweet, schmedium-sized girl who came to PACC paralyzed and unable to move. Over time she has made improvements but she requires a special home! She is more mobile but still needs assistance with getting around. Here is what her foster mom had to say about her: Ponyo is very affectionate and loves to cuddle! She loves to play but has very limited mobility so tends to spend most of her time chewing on toys but be careful, she likes anything with fringe and will occasionally steal a shoe or two! Her activities are limited by her condition, but she is as active as a dog like her can be. She has a silly expression, her eyes are very tender and she is full of love. She is the perfect mix of Goofy, playful, loving, and clumsy! She gets so excited to see her humans that she wiggles her butt in a very funny fashion. Because she's a medical needs dog, she will need someone who is willing to offer yoga mats, traction to aid in her walking, willing to work on physical therapy and give her lots of love. A home without cats would be preferable and one that can slowly introduce her to other dogs as well! She is perfect for someone who is nurturing and enjoys taking care of others. She is not an independent dog and needs her person to be okay with that. If Ponyo is tugging on your heartstrings, make an appointment to meet her today.

Doc is learning that people coming to visit him is a good thing, since he gets to go outside to the park, and he gets lots of snacks. His favorite is cheese, please! Doc has made major improvements since being at PACC, but needs a foster or adopter who will continue to work with him on socialization and gaining confidence. animal.description: Butch is a sweet, young guy with soulful eyes and a past we'll never know about. Butch came to PACC as a stray in need of medical attention for some pretty serious wounds, but after spending some time in the clinic, he's on the mend and ready to get out of the shelter and into a home. Because of his wounds, Butch hasn't been to play group with other pups yet, but during his behavioral evaluation he was easy to leash up and walked nicely. He's friendly with handlers and staffers tell us he's a happy and easygoing boy. Butch doesn't react to other dogs in the kennel and is a really laid back guy. Volunteers say he enjoys pets, scratches and treats (who doesn't) and is a very sweet boy. If Butch has already won your heart, don't waste any more time and make an appointment to meet him today.

animal.description: Sasha is a sweet girl who came to PACC for some medical issues, which turned out to be an undiagnosed case of diabetes. After spending some time in our clinic, her glucose levels are now under control and she's ready to find her forever home. Sasha's former owners said that she lived with other dogs and has experience with young children. Since coming to PACC, she's been sweet with volunteers and staffers, but a little bit unsure about the other dogs (the kennel can be a bit overwhelming.) While she can be a little nervous, Sasha is definitely friendly and does well with calm dogs and a little bit of time to warm up and get comfortable. Sasha was mostly an outdoor dog in her former home, but given her great manners, we know she'd make a great in-home companion. Sasha has spent some time in a foster home, and her foster said the following: -	She loves to play ball and will give the ball back -	She likes to chew on cow hooves and antlers -	She walks well on a leash -	She cuddles -	She is house and crate trained

animal.description: WORDS FROM KARMA'S FOSTER MOM :) The worlds biggest brightest smile belongs to... Little Miss Karma!!!!! But this is not the happy Karma I have always known. Karma found her self at the shelter sometime ago. She did so poorly there she had stopped eating and was walking in circles in her kennel. Before that she had been a yard dog, so shelter life was a really tough adjustment. She was completely shutting down, like she had given up all hope. She needed out desperately! In a home she changed quickly and dramatically. She became this silly,happy,smiling girl. And then she found herself a new home. But unfortunately, this home was not to last. Her person had to give her up for health reasons. I just couldn't let her go back to the shelter, so once again she has come back with me to look for her forever home. At four years old (OK -pushing 5) you would think Karma would be starting to slow down, but that is hardly the case. She is such a super happy, high energy, playful little wiggle butt. She just loves chasing a ball and playing tuggies, but her favorite thing is water. It can be a sprinkler, a hose or the pool. But she's not keen on taking any high dives off the end of my big pool. She much prefers her kiddie pool! When she does blossom, she can be a little bit of a diva. Karma is just starting to be a snuggle bug and she lets you know how happy she is with her full body wags and little bop kisses. She wants to be with you all the time and would probably be happiest as your one and only. Though Karma has had quite some troubles and disappointments in her life, you can tell by the smile on her face that she is an optimist. Both she and I are both determined to find her perfect home. Bonus- she is cat tested and approved! To learn more about Karma please email her foster mom Robin at rldaniels18@gmail.com or pacc.foster@pima.gov.

animal.description: Dino-mite!! Dino is a handsome boy with the most beautiful markings and a perfect round spot on his back. Dino is a nice boy with a fairly calm demeanor who enjoys treats and is very polite and gentle when taking them. FOSTER Q and A: Housetrained? Yes. Details on training: He pulls a little. He's great in his crate. He is super calm when he is in it and we cover it. He seems to like going there to relax for short periods of time. He's really good at sitting and gentle taking treats. He likes to chew on flavored bones. He walks around the dinner table for a minute when we are eating dinner but once he is ignored' he just goes back to his bed. Describe cuddling behavior/affection level: He absolutely loves to cuddle and loves to give kisses. We can put a pillow on his butt and lay there with him. He doesn't mind. Describe play behavior and favorite toys: He likes playing alone or with a person. He likes a squeaky duck. Describe activity level: Medium Look into the dog's eyes. What is he/she telling you? I just want to be loved and love you. What are the best adjectives to describe this dog? Funny, loving, sweet, cuddly,smart, obedient, and a character. What does the dog specifically DO that exemplifies those adjectives? Loving. He lets us hug him, give him kisses on his face and head, and lay on his butt. What are the dog's best qualities? Smart and loving What are your favorite things about this dog? Cute behaviors? He cracks me up when he sits in front of me, looks at me, and waits for a scratch. What is/are your favorite physical characteristic(s) of this of this dog? His brown spots on his eyes and one on his back. He reminds me of the dog on the Little Rascals movie. What would the ideal home look like for this dog? A home who truly love dogs and understand that stray dogs have probably gone through some trauma and so he will need a lot of love, guidance, consistency, and understanding. Anything else that would make this dog stand out to an adopter? I have severe arthritis and although he's a big dog, I have been able to handle him. Being around him helps my pain. He's so lovable and patient. We would keep him if we could. Email his foster to ask about him! - Linda: purplelight70@gmail.com

animal.description: We know from experience that blind dogs not only survive, they thrive! Meet sweet Seline. She's back at the shelter now, but she spent time in a foster home and here is what they had to say about her: Seline is truly one of the sweetest and well behaved dogs that I have been around, and she is such a character! She is blind but since we have had her since April, she has learned to navigate around the house and backyard (but definitely still bumps into things but she handles it like a champ! Lol). She is diabetic and requires insulin twice a day, but it is so easy to do and she sits like a perfect angel when we're giving it to her. She has been around cats at her last foster and I believe did well with them. She has been living with my dog who is a smaller Beagle/Dachshund mix and they get along and will play occasionally. I did introduce her to my mom and sisters dogs, both males, one is a pitbull and one a German Shepherd - and she seemed a little nervous around them, so maybe a house with smaller dogs or no other dogs would be best for her. We do not have her in a crate ever, and she is great in the house and has never destroyed anything other than her toys. She gets on the furniture only when invited on, but absolutely loves her orthopedic bed I, and will lounge on it and chew on her toys all day long. She does prefer to be in the same room as you when you are home. She also loves to go on short walks, but is strong on the leash. I have also learned that she loves to play in the water! When Seline met others dogs at PACC she was social, appropriate and tolerant. She explored the play yard on her own but was also interested in the other dogs. She also enjoyed playing in the water! Plase ask about fostering ro adopting this very deserving dog!!

animal.description: Foster Q and A! (Cont.) 7.	What are the animal's best qualities? Despite everything she's been through, Sufi just absolutely LOVES people. She is trusting with humans and has so much love to give. She is an incredible dog. 8.	What are your favorite things about him or her? Cute behaviors? Sufi has the cutest snore and she has the funniest lean - sometimes she'll lean back to try to lay closer to you and just falls right over. It's so funny and adorable! 9.	What is/are your favorite physical characteristic(s) of this of this animal? She has absolutely beautiful eyes and coloring - and her EARS are SO SOFT. 10.	What would the ideal home look like for him/her? Sufi would probably love a home where she can have lots of people to love her and shower her with affection! We guess that she would thrive with kids or a family, and she probably wouldn't mind being the center of attention as a solo dog or with a resident cat. 11.	Anything else that would make this animal stand out to an adopter? We cannot stress how sweet this girl is with people - everyone that meets her falls in love with her gentle personality. Medical/Behavior Issue 1.	Any medical issues? Sufi is going through the process of getting a brace for her back leg with A Loyal Companion! She has been fitted and shoud receive the brace at the end of January. This will help her with a calcified joint/previous injury on her right back leg. She is currently on CycloSPORINE. She gets around well despite her joint and leg issues and is overall a very happy gal. 2.	Any behavior issues? Sufi is picky about her dog friends and must have a meeting at PACC if there is another dog in the home. Her notes also included a mention of resource guarding, though we haven't experienced this ourselves first-hand.

animal.description:
Lulu is a sweet and calm love bug. She can be shy at first, but her wagging tail gives her away almost instantly! She is a one-year-old, 62 pound, black and white boxer mix, looking for a new home! Could it be with you?

Her favorite place to be is sitting right beside you, with her head on your chest or in your lap. She does fantastic when riding in a car and sits like a little human! She is crate trained AND potty trained! She also knows the command “sit”. Way to go, Lulu!

She walks on leash surprisingly gently for her size, but a confident handler would be a great plus for her to become even better and reliable on leashed walks.

She is great with people and kids. Lulu LOVES men!!! However, she will show reactive behaviors around other dominant dogs, so she will do best in a home with a very submissive dog or as the only dog in the home! If you do choose her as your one and only, she’ll never stop saying thank you with butt wiggles & sweet kisses and will make you a wonderful companion!

Lulu is very calm. She does not jump up unless invited, and maintains cool and collected when new people enter her space. She settles down nicely and can enjoy a long nap with the best of them! If you are looking for a couch potato, love bug, she might be the gal for you!

If Lulu attended Hogwarts, we believe she would be a Hufflepuff. She has kind eyes, loyalty to her people, and has a tenacious spirit that we think her future forever home will admire most of all!

If you are interested in adopting Lulu please go to our website to get the approval process started by completing our online pre-adoption application http://www.southernskiesrescue.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Max is such a cuddly guy. He wants to be with his people! He has such a sad story to share, but he's living in the moment and is a great pet! Max came into rescue after his person passed away from cancer. He was an animal lover and when he passed there were seven living together - Prince, Lady, Daisy, Bo, Roscoe, Brutus, and Max. They are not bonded to one another but enjoy the company of other pets and so far, all have tested great with cats, (respectful) kids, and all adults. They appear housetrained, crate trained or crate tolerant, and enjoy some snuggles on or near your lap! Because we are foster based, we require an approved application becasue a meet and greet can be scheduled. We think that is fair to our foster and the pet so every meet and greet has the potential to result in an immediate adoption! The application is available on the rescue website and can be completed online. We work with many rescues and strive to find every rescued dog in our care a great home. Sometimes that means transferring that pet to another location where adoption may be more likely. We currently have partners in New York, Pennsylvania, and Vermont.

If you are interesting in meeting any of our pets, the process is to complete an application. It can be downloaded as a pdf document from our website and submitted by email to WindyRidgeRescue@gmail.com as a scanned document or as photos OR can be completed entirely online. Both links are in the header of our website.

Because we are foster based, we require an approved application to schedule a meet and greet. We feel that is fair to our fosters and rescues so every meet and greet can result in an adoption.

We do not have set adoption fees for dogs, but hope adopters will donate generously so we can rescue more. The medical care for every dog can easily exceed the adoption donation. Average adoption fees for dogs in the area range from $175 up to $450.

We ask for a minimum adoption donation of $50 for cats regardless of age. Each cat is up to date on vaccinations, dewormer, and microchipped. Larger donations are always welcome so we can rescue more. Medical care for each cat easily exceeds the minimum donation.

As with every rescue, our resources are limited and the need for rescue help is unlimited. Your generosity helps us to rescue more.

Adopting or fostering for a rescue frees up a space where a new rescue can reside.

If you can't adopt or foster, than please consider donating.

animal.description:
Meet Siri! She is an about 2.5 years old, 88 pound ridgeback/plott hound mix. She came to us as a puppy with mange (she has a few tiny scars but is BEAUTIFUL and fully healed years ago) and was adopted but through no fault of her own is back with Maxx & Me looking for a forever home. She is a very smart girl who knows basic commands, loves to be cuddled, and play with her toys. She is potty trained and behaves nicely in the house. She pulls a little on leash but is easy to redirect and just needs a little work. Siri needs a 6' fenced in yard to play in. She has medium energy so would be great to go for walks or adventures then just chill next to her people. She loves everyone she meets!! She is good with other dogs but fine as an only. No small animals or small kids because she doesn't seem to understand that she is quite a big girl and really wanted to play with a chihuahua she met so we don't want anyone to accidentally get hurt. Siri spayed, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Adoption applications can be found on www.maxxandme.org. Adoption donation is only $250!
Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue. 1/29/21 11:55 AM

All dogs are up to date on vaccines (Distemper, Rabies, Bordetella), microchipped, spayed/neutered and receive worming, flea & tick medication before they are adopted out. Please note there are some exceptions depending on the condition of the dog. If you are interested in this dog please fill out an online application at https://www.camppapillon.org/dog-application.

Once your dog is in your home, they will adjust and relax and could become more playful or show more personality traits as they begin to open up. Once adopted, please allow your dog time to decompress and relax in a stable home environment.

animal.description:
Bogie came to us from a family that found him on the streets so we don't know very much about him other than that he is a sweet, lovable boy that thinks he's a lap dog despite his size.  In the familys home that found him he slept and ate with another dog, met her 3 year old niece and was such a good boy.  He's played well with nearly every dog that he's met here since we have gotten him, he is unneutered still and has only shown a dislike for another unneutered male.  

Bogie loves to run in the fields, he has a lot of energy to burn off!  He is a bit of an escape artist though and has escaped 2 crates while here so now he gets to relax and sleep in one of our suites.  Bogie loves to be around people and isn't keen on being alone still, would do best with someone who is home frequently (at least in the beginning) until he gets used to his new routine.  Bogie will be ready to go home and will be fully vaccinated and neutered by mid February, but he is ready to meet his forever family today!

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Thor! My Foster Mom calls me Tory. I am 2 years old and about 42lbs Shepard Mix. 
Originally from Vermillion Parish and confiscated from a cruelty case, but me and some friends hitched a ride back to New Orleans with my foster mom. I vaguely remember my past life because I have been getting so much love at my foster home where I have made some friends. 
I must say that I love everyone and every dog. I’m very charming and no dog can resist me. I can’t help it! My wish list includes: an active home with other dogs preferably. I don’t really dig cats, but kids are my jam. 
If you enjoy running, well I would love to run with you! If you enjoy throwing balls for me to catch we will get along so great. 
I am being treated for heart-worm and already scheduled to get neutered on 1/28/2021. 
I am really looking for my forever home, and I’ll tell you a secret I like wearing costumes. When it’s cold I won’t mind wearing sweaters. 
So now just go fill out an adoption application so we can meet soon. 
I must warn though my foster mom says you will fall in love with me on the spot. So be prepared!”

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

The NMDR Rehab Team is working with Phyllis to help her work through some behavior challenges. She needs a family who will be extra patient with her, and who preferably has previous experience with dogs. To submit an application to adopt Phyllis, visit https://nmdr.org/our-dogs/adopt/

Prior to being rescued, many of our dogs have experienced minimal socialization. As a result, there is often an adjustment period when learning about life as a family pet. We typically do not adopt dogs to homes with young children. Homes with older children will be considered on an individual basis. Common skills such as house training and leash walking will often take a little extra time. Patience, understanding and a gentle hand are a must. The great news is, most of these dogs come around rather quickly and being a part of their rehabilitation is an extremely rewarding experience. Learn about mill dogs and fill out an application at our website: http://nmdr.org

animal.description: Netherwood is a 1-2 yr old Pit bull mix. She is loose, wiggly and happy! Netherwood is high energy which means she would need plenty of exercise and playtime. She pulls on a leash but with some basic obedience training, this could easily be resolved. She is food motivated. Netherwood knows the sit command. She is NOT a fan of cats in a shelter atmosphere. Dogs are generally tested with dogs of their own size; and dog meets with the resident dogs are always encouraged. Our cat test should be used as a general purpose screening only to rule out overt aggression; we always recommend caution when introducing dogs to cats in the home. Recommendation on suitability of placement with children by their ages is based on behavioral observations including energy level and response to body handling. We never recommend leaving young children unsupervised with dogs, and we cannot guarantee the behavior of dogs with children, other pets or cats. Behavior evaluations should be considered as a snapshot of the behavior of the dog at this point in time; JHS believes all dog families need to be prepared to invest time and energy into training as well as provide common sense management of their new dog. We always encourage family to do some research on the breeds or mixes of breeds prior to adoption as many can have some unique characteristics that may or may not fit into their families. Always remember that the majority of dogs at our shelter have been exposed to or may have kennel cough. Kennel cough is contagious to other dogs, please talk to your vet if you have any questions about kennel cough prior to adoption. Please ask your adoption counselor at time of adoption if you have any unanswered questions regarding illnesses and treatments of the path that you are adopting. For more information about this dog or any others at our Shelter, please visit www.joplinhumane.org. We are the Joplin Humane Society in Joplin, Missouri. 417-623-3642 I AM SPONSORED! Thank you Darcy Robison for sponsoring me!

animal.description:
Bo is a fine fellow! He has such a sad story to share, but he's living in the moment and is a great pet! Bo came into rescue after his person passed away from cancer. He was an animal lover and when he passed there were seven living together - Prince, Lady, Daisy, Bo, Roscoe, Brutus, and Max. They are not bonded to one another but enjoy the company of other pets and so far, all have tested great with cats, (respectful) kids, and all adults. They appear housetrained, crate trained or crate tolerant, and enjoy some snuggles on or near your lap! Because we are foster based, we require an approved application becasue a meet and greet can be scheduled. We think that is fair to our foster and the pet so every meet and greet has the potential to result in an immediate adoption! The application is available on the rescue website and can be completed online. We work with many rescues and strive to find every rescued dog in our care a great home. Sometimes that means transferring that pet to another location where adoption may be more likely. We currently have partners in New York, Pennsylvania, and Vermont.

If you are interesting in meeting any of our pets, the process is to complete an application. It can be downloaded as a pdf document from our website and submitted by email to WindyRidgeRescue@gmail.com as a scanned document or as photos OR can be completed entirely online. Both links are in the header of our website.

Because we are foster based, we require an approved application to schedule a meet and greet. We feel that is fair to our fosters and rescues so every meet and greet can result in an adoption.

We do not have set adoption fees for dogs, but hope adopters will donate generously so we can rescue more. The medical care for every dog can easily exceed the adoption donation. Average adoption fees for dogs in the area range from $175 up to $450.

We ask for a minimum adoption donation of $50 for cats regardless of age. Each cat is up to date on vaccinations, dewormer, and microchipped. Larger donations are always welcome so we can rescue more. Medical care for each cat easily exceeds the minimum donation.

As with every rescue, our resources are limited and the need for rescue help is unlimited. Your generosity helps us to rescue more.

Adopting or fostering for a rescue frees up a space where a new rescue can reside.

If you can't adopt or foster, than please consider donating.

Wendi has come a long way since her arrival on November 9th, but still has a long way to go. Wendi came into ODAAT completely feral. She is still fearful and cautious with people, cars, and noises. animal.description:
Looking for someone to spend your days with? Someone who is always waiting for you at the door when you get home? A workout buddy? Motivation to get your daily steps in? Someone to snuggle on the couch with? Poppy is your girl!



Poppy is a well-rounded girl of 7 years. Her hobbies include walks, pets, begging for snacks, and napping. Her signature move is to walk up to you, sit on your feet, and look up at you over her head with big puppy dog eyes, begging for a little love. She is a sweet girl who can get excited and chase you around the living room. She'll crawl right up into your lap and let you hold her like a little baby (she doesn't realize she is 80lbs). Though she's not interested in toys, she is interested in you goofing around the family room floor. But if you're looking for some quiet time, she quickly gets the picture and will join you in that nap. When she sleeps, she is an active dreamer. You'll catch her chasing after squirrels or whimpering at the moon in her sleep. She might wake you up with her chasing paws if you're sharing a bed!



Initially she is interested in your tasty human food, but quickly realizes it is not for her and will go lay down while her humans eat. Poppy is a quick learner. She just wants to follow her humans around the house helping with whatever she can. Whether you're vacuuming, cooking, attempting yoga, or watching TV, Poppy is by your side (or in your downward dog) lending her support! She is the perfect example of a dog's unconditional love.
animal.name: Poppy

animal.description:
Riley is with a trainer. He needs a foster or foster to adopt who can help him learn to control his impulsive nature. He is looking for someone with previous German Shepherd expirence. He will need a stong handler who can set rules and boundaries and can hold him accountable. He could do well with another dog with proper guidence. He needs a slow intro to new people, but is gaining confidence in this area. He very much wants to please but gets overstimulated easily.

For more information email mitliebegsdr@gmail.com or fill out an application on our website www.mlgsdr.com

*Disclaimer, we're providing what information we know and what has been passed along by previous owners, shelters, etc. If the information you're looking for is not listed, please reach out and request more detail.

All dogs/puppies have been fully vetted including spay/neuter, micro-chipping, worming, heartworm testing, and preventative treatment, and all required age appropriate vaccinations. As required by Wisconsin Act 90, all dogs will have received a veterinarian exam (CVI) within the past 30 days, prior to finalizing the adoption. We reserve the right to not adopt to homes with children under the age of 7 years old. We also offer free beginner obedience classes (in Green Bay, WI) for any dog adopted from us.

We always recommend crate training, exercise, playtime and a regular schedule for potty breaks when bringing a new dog into your home. Adjustment takes time for both you and your new family member, so remember to be patient.


Mit Liebe German Shepherd Dog Rescue License #272376-DS

animal.description:
JAIME: 15 week old, 26lbs (as of 1/10), Lab/Hound Mix, Neutered Male (Estimated to be about 50lbs Full Grown), HIGH ACTIVE

He's got a ways to go physically and emotionally before he grows into those dinner plate sized feet. Jaime is a little timid and cant imagine hell be big and strong one day soon. Hes quickly set atremble by noises on the street, hes intimidated by the city and a wallflower around new people. Behind closed doors where hes comfy though, this 4-month-old lab/hound mix melts into a cuddle puddle. Boosting his confidence and minimizing the stress triggers will be key to helping him grow into a well adjusted young buck, so hell need to join a family with primary pup ownership experience out of the city or in a suuuuuuuuper quiet area. Jaime is smart, playful, and good with other dogs, but hell need some guidance on trusting the world around him. A little pro training could help. Hes around 24 lbs now and will likely hit 50 to 60 lbs, possibly more, when hes done growing. Hard to say. Hes got a big brain and lots of energy to burn, so tons of exercise and games (90 minutes a day plus) will be crucial. Intrested in adopting? Please go to www.socialteesnyc.org 

His Foster Says: Jaime has so much love to give but isn't confident enough to show it just yet. What he does live for are soft cuddles and loving head rubs, specifically right behind his ear - that's the sweet spot! He feels most comfortable cuddled up on his dog bed or his favorite place, the couch! Head propped up on a pillow is where he likes to take his naps. Even though Jaime has a lot of energy, he isn't a city boy just yet so short walks is what he feels the most comfortable with, so he really likes to play at home with his favorite tennis ball, lamby, or bone. Overall, Jaime is also one of the smartest (and cutest) puppies I have ever met, and has already mastered going up and down flights of stairs! 

Please welcome JAIME and his siblings to NYC. These puppies are our latest litter of working breed heartbreakers. You might look at thier faces and be like OMG I need that ASAP. But due to thier breed mix these babies need a very particular home. They need a home with primary dog experience (meaning that you have owned or been solely responsible for a dog as an adult). Growing up with dogs is very different to being fully responsible for a dog as an adult (sorry to burst your bubbles/dreams so early in the year). These guys are very fast learners which means they need adopters who are going to be up to the task of keeping thier little brains active and stimulated so that they don't become bored trouble markers. As full grown adults you can expect these babies to need a minimum of 90 minutes of outdoor exercise. Hound mixes are notorious for wanting to walk for days. Walking is thier love language. They are working on potty training skills and basic commands. They are good with other dogs and cats. They are not a good match for families with young kids as these guys are going to be going through teething. JAIME did come down with a cold when he first arrived in NYC but he is doing great: saw the vet, went on antibiotics and his appetite and energy level hasn't been affected :) Interested in adopting please go to www.socialteesnyc.org 
 

What is a hound?: Hounds were originally bred as the first hunting companions. They are known for their ability to track by scent and are a high energy kind of pup that need to practice using their nose. We can't think of a breed more excited to go for a walk than a hound. They love to be able to get out daily and have a good sniff. Hounds are known for being highly intelligent and fast runners.

\What does owning this dog entail?: Tons of socialization, exercise, and mental stimulation is crucial. This dog is considered a working breed since their original purpose was to do a job. It's going to be very important to keep this pup busy both physically and mentally -- that includes a minimum of 90 minutes of outdoor time every day for this high energy dog. A perfect walking, hiking, and running buddy. We strongly recommend a basic training course to get a more solid feel for this pup's individual needs and how to best communicate with each other. A well trained dog is a happy dog. Hounds are the best snugglers in our experience, and they are great dogs for active outdoorsy people. Heads up they tend to have high prey drive though, so adults are often quick to go for small animals like squirrels and not great choices for homes with cats or other small animals. They can also be very stop and go walking buddies sometimes because of that crazy nose of theirs, so some hounds require extra leash training -- they literally want to stop and smell every little thing. They are also quick to take off if they catch a scent, so you have to be extra careful with hounds off leash because they will disappear if you haven't done enough recall training with them -- or even if you have sometimes, their instincts just take over. We strongly recommend not having them off leash in an unenclosed area.

PLEASE NOTE: This animal is not at the Social Tees office all of our dogs and cats are in foster homes while they wait to find their forever families. :) If youd like to apply to adopt this pet, please complete an adoption application at socialteesnyc.org. Because we are a small team and receive hundreds of applications each week, we are unable to respond to every application and every inquiry email, but we do our best. Please have patience! If your application is approved, you will for sure hear from us. If you have questions, please take a look at the Adoption and Fostering FAQs etc. on our website as all common questions are answered there. Thank you for your understanding and flexibility as we work to save these innocent lives!! 

LEARN MORE ABOUT US: socialteesnyc.org; Instagram via @socialteesnyc; Facebook.com/socialteesanimalrescue

COURTESY POST.

MEET BABY! 
This very handsome pit mix is seeking a new forever home due to personal circumstances of the present owner.

animal.description:
Please only send inquires to the email in this bio all others will not be answered. Please read the bio before sending questions - we answer all we know about the dog here.

Hi I'm Niko!! I'm a 3-4 year old Chihuahua. I was found on a highway and a really nice man stopped his car blocking traffic to save me. I am now in a foster home and I am loving life. I love my doggie and kitty brothers and sisters. I really love my crate and dog bed and can find me always lounging in there. I love food!! Don't let my tiny physique fool you, I will take down a Buffalo and eat it whole if i could. I love meal time and may whine a bit if you're not fast enough but i never bark!! I don't think foster mom has ever heard me bark.

I am potty trained and love going outside to explore but i won't go far as I like being close to my human. I am allergic to fleas so I'll need monthly prevention to prevent me from breaking out and scratching myself raw. I am a lover not a fighter and love giving my human kisses. I am looking for a forever home where I'll be cherished forever and and kept safe. I will love you forever!!!

Niko is utd on vaccinations, on flea/hw preventative and scheduled to be neutered and microchipped.

Niko's adoption fee is $400 - obedience training is required after adoption

Obedience training is also required for all our pups. We understand with what is going on in the world that this may be a bit delayed. Please email us the completion certificate.

To apply to foster or adopt please fill out application at

www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

Thank you for completing the application. We are all volunteers and short on time, we will contact you back only if we have more questions or your application is approved and you will be invited to meet the dog. We apologize for not being able to answer everyone back.

For more information contact Kelly.V@HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

DOGS are in Foster Homes. There is NO shelter.

**Our companions MUST live in your home as part of your family.**We do not transport.

**See our website for more information. www.HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

All communication is thru email so please be patient with us. We are all volunteers and work full time jobs and have families of our own.

It takes anywhere between 3-7 days to process an application - the more complete the application the easier it is for us to process it. Please notify your vet that we will be contacting them and to release information to us.

ADOPTION PROCESS:

1. Complete this application
www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

***Everyone must submit an application - we only keep them on file for 1 month

2. Application background check, vet check, etc

3. Invitation thru email to meet the dog(s).

4. Adoption Contract

Age:1-3
Weight: 120
Location: Newtown, PA
Nicknames: Prunee, Wilda, Nellie
Good with other dogs?: Yes.
Comes on strong and a little rude but she is fine!
Good with cats? unknown, will not be adopted to a home with a cat
Good with children? unknown, will not be adopted to a home with kids under 10
Activity Preference: Needs a couple walks a day., Needs in-house activities, Up for a long hike any day.
IQ: Smart
Prunella's favorite things: Walks at the park, car rides, being with her peeps, food, food, snacks, food and snacks.
Prunella is good at: meeting people, meeting dogs, going for car rides, making me feel safe, walking on a leash, playing
Ideal home: someone at home most of the day, a fenced yard
Training Needs: needs obedience training
Health issues: As you can see from her photos, she was not well taken care of. There were many baths, antibiotics, ointments etc., to treat her horrible skin and eye infections. She is a high maintenance girl. She needs to go home with a family who understands the needs of a girl prone to skin issues.

Meet Prunella

Prunella is a Big, MESSY, Love. While she is adorable, she is a lot of work. She is the messiest drinker and after a few slurps, the floor is a sloshy pool of drool. She is needy and does not like to be crated at all but she does not have separation anxiety to the point of destroying things. She is just happy to be with people. She does need a bath every few days at least until she is 100% over her skin infections or she does develop quite a strong smell. She is totally sweet as sugar though and very funny. Foster mom labels her as very high maintenance.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hello! I'm Madonna. I'm big and fluffy and SUPER shy, but once I get to know you, I'll let you pet me, especially if you have some of my favorite treats. I'm also attending some classes that work on shyness and fear.

Here are some things that need in my new home:

1.) A big fenced in yard where I can roam and play with my new canine siblings.

2.) Other dogs as they help me relax.

3.) Patient and calm human(s) who will let me acclimate at my pace.

I recently started to get playful with my foster dad. Sometimes when he comes in the room, I'll turn a circle a couple times, go up to him, and playfully paw at him. I'm still nervous around him and will occasionally run out of the room when he enters, but I'm doing a lot better thanks to my foster siblings, my patient human, and my shyness classes. If you think we might be a good match, please apply to adopt me.

When we meet, I may even let you pet me!

I can't wait to meet you!

~Madonna

Good with Dogs: Yes

It's hard not to fall in love with Hamlet. This sweet boy is so laid back and loveable! His favorite things are getting pets, sleeping, rolling around in the yard and he gets very excited about breakfast and dinner. While Hamlet cannot see, he doesn't let that dull his spirits or stop him from getting around just fine. He also gets along well with other dogs in his foster home. Don't miss out on his big smile and his adorable little excitement hops, they're the best!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
Mimi
Female - spay date 1/28/21
Italian Greyhound / Chihuahua mix
Born 2017

Weight:  9 pounds
Adoption Fee:  $195

NMAF ADOPTION APPLICATION, found at www.nmaf.org/adopt/adoption-application.

Please complete an Adoption Application if you are interested in Mimi.

Mimi came to NMAF when her mom passed away and the family could not keep her or her companions.  Coming from a rural shelter in NM, she was terribly frightened and confused.  Her other companions were taken by another rescue, so are safe.  Mimi's distress caused her to come down with kennel cough, even though she was only in the shelter 1 day, but she is now healthy after treatment and ready to meet her new family.  Mimi has the beautiful long-legged and slender form of an Italian Greyhound but the pixie-ish face and head of a Chihuahua.  At 9 pounds, she is all legs!  She loves her new foster home, especially Dad, whom she snuggles with every morning while he enjoys his coffee.  She learned the doggie door very quickly, sleeps quietly in a crate, and has nice manners in the home.  She loves to bark at her neighbors dogs, so it is not recommended that she live in an apartment, but she would love a quiet home with a secure fence & yard, especially with another playful doggy companion.  We have learned this little girl can jump, so her yard needs a 6 ft. fence and gates that cannot be breached.  At 3 yrs. old, she still has plenty of energy and playfulness, and she loves to go for walks every day.  She is perfect for an active retired couple who can give her the love, attention, and security she needs.  Children under 10 are not recommended.  She cannot be spayed until 1/28/21 due to a backlog at veterinarians right now, but if the right family is found, she could go into a Foster-to-Adopt home with NMAF covering the cost of her remaining medical needs.  An APPLICATION is required to arrange a meet & greet.  Her adoption fee will be $195 which covers all shots, microchip, spay, & heartworm test.

More Info:  Contact Kate at kmolsbe@gmail.com.

animal.description: Murphy is a 25lb neutered male sable & white Sheltie. Our vet estimates that he is around 2-3 years old. Murphy got a rough start in life, and he is a very reserved guy who will need a patient adoptive family experienced with fearful dog rehabilitation. He suffers from the autoimmune condition dermatomyositis (or DMS). There is no cure for DMS, but the symptoms can be controlled with medication, a low-stress household and great nutrition. Shelties with DMS can live long, happy lives with understanding and supportive families. Murphy seems to prefer women over men, but he can be won over with treats. A very securely fenced yard is required for Murphy's adoptive home, and his adoptive family should be prepared to leash walk him inside of the fenced yard for additional safety for the first few weeks after adoption. If you're interested in meeting or adopting Murphy, please fill out an application via our website scsheltierescue.com. His adoption donation of $300 includes neuter, all vaccinations and microchip. FEBRUARY 2021

animal.description: Are you looking for a Little love in your life? Look no further than the Little puppies! These sweet girls are playful, snuggly and just a bit mischievous. They came to Labs and More without a mom or dad so we aren't quite sure what their breed mix is or how big they will get. We are guessing they will stay on the smaller side. Smidge bounces around like Tigger and loves to play! Smidge is looking for a family that understands the time, patience, and energy needed to raise a young pup. We require all puppy adopters to provide training that includes: house training, basic training, leash training, and socialization. Additionally, this cutie is going to need proper exercise, mental stimulation, and your attention and love to grow up to be the best companion. We do not allow our dogs or puppies to sleep or live outside; they must be incorporated into your family and be made a priority in your life. In return, you will have the most loving and loyal family member you could ask for. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting a puppy, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
Scrap 
After months of nurturing, tests and getting her diabetes leveled out, she is now ready for adoption! Special thank you to SO SO many people that donated and supported this girl. Call out to Tom and Laura House that funded a large portion of her treatment 
Bio from Julie Neville her AMAZING foster 
Very sweet older girl looking for a retirement home! Scrap is just about the perfect dog. Scrap very quiet, and she is a very happy dog. She is about 12 years old. She loves attention and wags her tail so fast when she is near you. Scrap is also housebroken. Scrap has two minor issues which any potential adopter would need to be willing to accept. First of all, Scrap is blind. Once she learns the layout of your house, she gets around very well and can even do stairs. Second of all, Scrap is diabetic. But please don't think that her diabetes is a daunting issue. Two meals a day and two insulin shots and she is good to go! Scrap does require a special food due to her diabetes which is a prescription food you can get from your vet's office. It is estimated that the total cost for her insulin, syringes, and prescription food would amount to approximately $130 per month. Scrap would love a quiet home (maybe with another older dog?) to spend her retirement years.Please submit an Adoption Application here: www.rocthedogsrescue.com

animal.description:
LOOKING FOR THE PERFECT HOME!!

Tiny Tim . Ready for the perfect hospice home/adoption.

In rescue the hardest thing can be saying goodbye to some of the most precious souls. If we don't do this, we deny another animal in need the space and care it also deserves .

Tiny Tim has roughly 1 year to live based on the doctors diagnosis. With that said, he is doing quite well on all his medications and the doctors have him comfortable:)

At 5.5lbs...he is very much like a little baby. I change his diapers a 5-8 times a day. He poos on a pee pad and needs cough and pain meds every 8 hours. His other meds every 12 hours. He begs for food. Prefers fresh pet for his meals and can get raging jealous of his siblings . He loves to snuggle and requires quite a few deep sleep naps during the day.

He suffers from severe mitral valve disease and his back has been broken and fused together. His heart ailment will eventually take his life.

Our goal is to keep him comfy, as pain free as possible and happy as long as possible. We are looking for a compassionate, quiet home where he can be spoiled rotten and give you soooo much love in return .Please submit an Adoption Application here: www.rocthedogsrescue.com

animal.description:
Name: Howie (fka King)
Suspected Breed: Bulldog Mix
Approximate Age: 10 years old
Approximate Weight: 76 lbs
Personality: Friendly and sweet	
Observations with Dogs: good with other dogs
Observations with Cats: not yet tested
Observations with Kids: not yet tested
Currently Living at: DMV-area foster

Check out Howie's adoption video here: https://youtu.be/yd4bQyqmuKs
 
Who can resist that silver muzzle? Howie is a senior fellow whose owner was moving and surrendered him to the PG County shelter. He would like to spend his golden years in a warm and loving home. Howie is friendly and affectionate. He considers himself a lapdog and will attempt to sit in your lap despite his 76lbs! He is not very tall but is built like a tank. Despite his age, he is spry and loves toys and playing fetch. He was calm and cautious when introduced to other dogs. We have not tested him with kitties yet. 

Howie is a smart boy eager to please. He knows ""come"", ""sit"", and ""speak"". He's done well with crate training and house training and has good manners. Howie loves to sleep on the sofa curled up next to his foster and snores like bulldogs (and old fellas) often do. Despite having been left at a shelter in his old years, he maintains a very friendly and happy disposition. He's excited to find his forever family so that he can live out his golden years in a loving home. 

Like most shelter dogs, Howie may need a refresher on housetraining and crate training. We ask all of DC PAWS' fosters to work on both house and crate training with their foster dog.

The adoption fee for senior dogs is $200. If you are interested in adopting Howie, please submit an adoption application at https://dcpawsrescue.org/adoption-info/adoption-application-dogs/ABOUT US & IMPORTANT DISCLOSURES:

Please note that you must use our official adoption application in order to be considered for adoption. Applying through other sites (i.e., Petfinder) will not work. The following are our applications:

Dog application: https://service.sheltermanager.com/asmservice?account=bg0781&method=online_form_html&formid=1
Cat application: https://service.sheltermanager.com/asmservice?account=bg0781&method=online_form_html&formid=6

DC PAWS Rescue does our best to provide accurate and complete information about our adoptable animals. Please note that we cannot make any guarantees about age or breed; we rely upon our rescue partners and their veterinarians to make those assessments. We also cannot make any guarantees about housebreaking and animal temperament, as animals can behave differently through transition and in different environments.

Our shelter partners provide a basic vet screening for each animal we rescue, which includes necessary vaccinations, deworming, microchipping, and spay/neuter (unless the animal is too young or otherwise deemed by the vet to not be a good candidate for surgery). Please note that this is not a comprehensive medical exam and as such, may not identify any and all medical issues, though our goal is to flag any obvious health issues through the basic vet screening. We share all medical records with adopters and are completely transparent about any known issues prior to adoption finalization. 

ABOUT DC PAWS RESCUE

Our rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based dog and cat rescue in the DC area. We rescue locally from Prince Georges County, MD, and from rural shelters in the south (presently Pickens County, Anderson County, and Greenville County in SC, and Raleigh County, WV).

We partner with a local rescuer in Pickens County, SC, who saves adoptable cats and dogs from the three area shelters. For the animals in this rural area, rescue is a critical lifeline, and often the only lifeline. Our rescue partner not only works with DC PAWS to save as many dogs and cats as possible, but she has also established a successful spay/neuter program in the community to decrease the number of homeless and unwanted animals over the long term.

FOSTER AN ANIMAL IN NEED

Fosters make it possible for DC PAWS to save and care for homeless, neglected and abandoned animals! To learn about fostering dogs or cats for DC PAWS Rescue, please visit: http://dcpawsrescue.org/volunteer/fostering/foster-application

SPONSOR AN ANIMAL IN NEED

For any of our animals! Sponsors help us provide critical medical care, food, boarding, and other support for animals facing euthanasia. Individuals who sponsor a dog or cat receive special recognition on the animal's profile. Sponsorships can also be made in honor or memory of a loved one, and you may designate to whom DC PAWS Rescue should provide notice of your gift. Sponsorship levels of $250 and $150 include ""naming rights"" for a future dog or cat (respectively) that we rescue.

To learn more about sponsorship, please visit: http://dcpawsrescue.org/donate/

His previous owner passed away and he has been stuck at a shelter for the past few months, so we had to rescue him! He is about 10 years old and weighs about 85 lbs, but he is extremely calm and mellow. Casper is house-trained, kennel trained, and is very well behaved. He's also super smart and knows sit, stay, and come. He loves to just laze around the house, get pets and he plays very gently with his smaller foster sibling. He enjoys going on walks and exploring, and has excellent leash manners. He is great with children (even toddlers)! He gets along with dogs and cats of all sizes/ages. Casper is recovering from a reaction to a grain allergy, so he will need to be fed a grain-free diet. Casper will be the best housemate youll ever have!

Donate at codysfriendsrescue.org to help us save more lives! https://codysfriendsrescue.org/donate

animal.description:
Hi! I am Rocco a 4.5 year old, 55 lb Basenji/lab mix looking for my forever family 3 I am UTD, neutered, house broken, crate trained adventure buddy!. I am high energy and would love a family that is active but also loves to cuddle. I require an experienced owner as I can be protective of certain things of high value and can like my space at times. I love love love other dogs, however I would do best in a home without kids. I have seen a cat before and I am not sure what to make of it. 

I have to find my new forever home because I am a retired star from Sea World and due to COVID my show was canceled. 

Adoption requirements are as such: 


	No apartments
	No children under 16 
	A home in Orlando 
	Not a first time dog owner 
	Resource guarding experience 
	No cats 


Please note, Rocco is part of Happy Trails Animal Rescues rehoming program. He has not been tested or evaluated and the information gathered is from the current owners personal statements regarding health and temperament. The owner is subject to placement outside of our organization. We cannot guarantee availability.
