animal.description:
Dale 
Male
1 1/2 years old 
45 pounds 
Mix 

Hi my name is Dale and Im a super sweet and very curious young pup. I havent had any accidents in the house since I came to Buffalo. I do awesome in my crate to sleep and when my foster parents leave for a few hours. When I first got here I didnt really understand what toys were but have caught on quick and now love playing ball (I doesnt always return it) and chewing bones and stuffed toys. I understand when you say no and am learning sit, leave it and other commands. My foster dad says I walk pretty good with a harness but love to look at everything and walk back and forth in front of his feet. I dont seem to mind the cold and love flinging the snow around. 

My foster mom gave me this thing called a bath when I first got here because I was really stinky and my pretty white coat was very dirty. I didnt like that much but have since stuck my head in the shower when shes in there so maybe water isnt that scary. 

I love to snuggle on the couch with my foster family and watch tv. I havent been around any little kids or cats but may be a little too much for either since I still act like a puppy. I get excited and sometimes jump. Im working on getting better. I seem to love other dogs but am still learning my boundaries. 

My foster families favorite things about me are my sweet puppy kisses and my smushy cute face.

If you are interested in Dale please apply at https://www.nickelcitycaninerescue.org/adopt-a-dog or message the rescue if you are already pre-approved.

animal.description:
Gorgeous 3 year old purebred male rottweiler. Great with kids. Grew up with young children in the house. He likes female dogs but hasn't been around too many males so we don't know how he does with males. He needs basic obedience training but is a well behaved boy in general and wants to please his owner. He will need to be neutered on the 25th of January, before he can be adopted. If you llive in the East valley then you might be able to foster him until you can adopt him on the 25th. 
Our Adoption Process... If you are interested in adopting one of our fun loving not so rotten rotties, you will be asked to fill out a questionnaire that will allows us to get to know you better and to make sure the dog you are looking at is a good fit for your family and lifestyle. You can access our questionnaire by going to our website, www.rottenrottie.com click on the forms tab, and fill out the questionnaire and submit it online. After we review your answers, if we feel that the dog that you are interested in, is not a good fit for you and your family, we may recommend a different rottweiler companion. After we determine which Rottweiler(s) is the best for you, we will set up a time so that you can meet him or her at their house, where they will feel most comfortable and act as they normally do. An adoption contract will be signed to finalize the adoption and we do ask for a rehoming fee of $400 for most adults, $250 for most of our seniors 6 years and above for any rottweiler mix of any age (except puppies) . Our fees for puppies fluctuate depending on how much we had to invest into them or their litter, and weather they are purebred or a mix. These funds are necessary so that our organization may continue to rehome rottweilers. ALL of our dogs are sterilized, fully vaccinated and microchipped, heartworm tested negative and come with a collar and a leash. We have also addressed any injury or illness that they had when they came to us, or received in foster care. These problems will be disclosed to the adopter prior to adoption.

animal.description:
Update: Nakoma is with a foster,  he is potty trained and sleeps all night snuggled in bed with him. He's a good boy, still anxious and decompressing after 6 days of freedom. He is scared of loud noises, becomes very anxious and jumps in a loud city environment when going for walks. He's being fostered in LA and needs a quiet neighborhood and setting to live in so if you don't live in the hustle n bustle areas, reach out for this deserving boy! 

This gorgeous blue eyed boy is one of our favorite and special rescues. He was just rescued after 7 months, yes I said 7 months of being locked up, passed up and was fed up of being kenneled. His name was Ren, he was depressed, mad and had given up! He was reported as hard to handle and no hope in sight until Alljoy4paws came and had faith in him that he was a good boy and just needed to trust again,  feel loved again and treated with kindness and respect. With this new chance comes a new life with a new name and he was named Nakoma which means great warrior and great spirit which he earned for making it out of the shelter after so long, especially for a husky. Nakoma was nothing that the shelter described, he walked out a little nervous and unsure what was happening but quickly realized he was saved and free. He jumped right into the car as fast as the door opened in the backseat and he raced to the passenger seat and called "Shotgun"! He road like a gem in the car and he smiled the whole way too! In fact, he never stopped smiling the 3.5hrs we were together. Check his pics! He might be a little cautious at first but warms up very quickly.  He wants that loving wonderful life that you can give him! He loves dogs and people and just wants to be part of the pack. He walks like a dream on a leash although given the chance to get loose from his collar, he was all about wanting to feel free and just run, I don't blame him after what he's been through. By the end of our time this hard to handle 5yr old was jumping up to give me gentle hugs and kisses. When he saw his new collar and leash, he gave them kisses, awwww!
He's decompressing right now and getting back to his fun self and ready for a great husky savvy foster or adopter to make all of his doggy wishes come true! Could that be you? We can't wait to hear from you!

animal.description: Lennox is the sweetest, calmest, and most adorable dog you'll ever meet, along with his sweetheart, Mountain (Mo). These pups lost their home when their owner passed away. Now, they're in foster and looking for a new forever home, hopefully together again. Lennox is a rottweiler/border collie mix with short legs. He's a little overweight, but on a diet in his foster home. He also appears to have some arthritis, but loves to go for walks with Mo and never slows down his hippity hop. At home, he'll sit on his foster's lap if she's on the floor, but can't jump up onto the couch to do it. He loves to lie in the yard and watch the world and squirrels go by. He's a well house-trained boy, very alert and always ready to go outside. He sleeps through the night on the carpet, and he sits on command! There's never a discouraging word out of this boy. He and Mo roughhouse at least once a day. Come meet him and Mo, they'll grab your heart!

animal.description: Introducing T-Bone, a handsome 18-month-old American Staffordshire Terrier mix who is looking for a second chance at being in a loving and nurturing home. T-Bone was abandoned by his owners and was not cared for very well. He needs a refresher course in house training, but he's very smart and should be house trained in no time. T-Bone lives with another dog in his foster home so he would do great in the home with other dogs, but he would prefer a cat-free home. T-Bone does fine when he's left on his own to roam in the home, and is not destructive in any way. He does well in a crate and is quiet and calm, which means you can relax knowing he is safe in his crate while you're out and about running your errands. T-Bone is very well mannered and it took him weeks to finally get up on the couch or bed with encouragement from his humans. He is very polite when accepting food. does not beg or steal. He will jump on humans only when he is very excited, but does this rarely and can easily be trained to stop this behavior. T-Bone loves human attention. He only wants to love and be loved! He enjoys being near you, touching you for affection. He enjoys meeting new people, and is very friendly and enjoys receiving pats. He likes to snooze on the bed or couch or on the deck in the sun. He's not much for toys, but is very playful. He is very calm and gentle and enjoys chilling and relaxing. T-Bone is mellow and patient and is willing to be trained. He would love a home with another dog to play with. He would love a calmer and less active home. He has cancer and is heartworm positive which means he will need low key activity and rest while he recovers from his heartworm treatment at APA's! expense. Are you able to teach T-Bone that humans are good and can be trusted? Come meet this sweet and loving boy today!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Elfie is a very pretty young, what we believe to be an Elk Hound mix male. He may be part Shepherd, part herding breed, we aren't sure, this is all speculation. But Elfie is young, and very active and has what seem like some herding instincts.
Elfie is sweet and affectionate and a great dog but he will need a household that can help him live out his activity drives, plenty of activity, motion, walks, dog park, etc. It would be ideal for him to romp around with another dog if possible or eventually. He does need a fenced in yard, he needs to move around and explore freely.

Elfie is @ 36 lbs, and @ 8 -9 months old.

On Elk Hounds:

Elkhounds are famously fine companions and intelligent watchdogs. Agility and herding trials are good outlets for their natural athleticism and eagerness. Reserved until introductions are made, an Elkhound is a trustworthy friend ever after. These strong, confident dogs are truly sensitive souls, with a dash of houndy independence.

If you are interested in Elfie see below, please fill out our form.

redemptionroadrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms

redemptionroad.mn@gmail.com

http://redemptionroadrescue.rescuegroups.org

All dogs age appropriate vetted:

Spayed or Neutered
Rabies vaccine
DHPP vaccine
4DX test (@8 months or older)
Microchipped
Dewormed
Flea/tick prevention

animal.description:
My name is Winston and I am a 4 year-young stunning pit bull with a great smile!  My hazel eyes drive the ladies crazy.  Woof, woof!!  I love to go on hikes and I also love long car rides.  Being scratched on my shoulders and butt are my favorite things in the whole wide world!  Woof!!  I also love spending the afternoon curled up on the couch watching TV next to my human.  Unfortunately, things haven’t always been easy for me.  My previous living situation was not the best and I wasn’t always treated well.  I heard my former dad was going to drop me on the streets because he got evicted from his home and he couldn’t keep me.  Luckily, that didn’t happen.  Grrrrr...

Enough about my past.  I’m looking forward to a bright future with my new family and friends.  I currently reside in Tustin, CA with my foster humans and foster brother Oz.  I get along with the mellow yellow kinda dogs with proper introduction and guidance, but please no puppies or dogs with high energy...or cats.  Oh yeah, don’t even get me started with cats!  I don’t want to live with an animal that poops in the house... yuck!

My personal trainer, Katie, is my BFF and has helped me a lot in just the month I’ve been living in Tustin.  She keeps telling me what a good boy I am.  I really am a good boy and love to please.  I don’t get bothered by skateboards or bicycles when I got for walks.  In fact, the lady that is taking care of me lets me trot next to her while she rides a razor... so cool!  Woof!!  

I really need someone with dog experience who can show me the ropes and show me true love.  Are you that special someone for me??  Please contact Shelli Dall with any questions at 619.818.0054.  I hope to meet you soon!  


Please help us get Winston into a safe, loving forever home!  If you're unable to help by adopting, sharing this post or donating is always appreciated.  Don't forget, Passion for Pitties is a 501(c)(3), so all donations are tax-deductible!…every little bit helps!
 
If you would like to adopt loving Winston, please fill out an application at www.passionforpitties.com under the “Adorable Adoptables” heading.

animal.description:
CINNABON THE NEWEST MEMBER OF OUR PACK WAS RESCUED BY ONE OF OUR LONG STANDING VOLUNTEERS WHOM HAD TO BEAR WITNESS TO THIS GIRL BEING PUSHED FROM A CAR LEFT ALONE WHILE HER PREVIOUS HUMAN DROVE AWAY WITHOUT HESITATION. IN DISGUST AND DISBELIEF SHE FOLLOWED PROTOCOL AND BROUGHT HER TO OUR OFFICE. 
BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN A CHRISTMAS PRESENT THAT WAS UNWANTED ONLY DAYS INTO THE NEW YEAR, THE PRIOR OWNER DECIDED TO DUMP HER AT A GAS STATION WHERE OTHERS WERE GUARANTEED TO SEE HER WONDERING AND IN NEED OF HELP. DESPITE INTENTIONS THIS IS OBVIOUSLY NOT ACCEPTABLE AND WE ARE GLAD THAT SHE DID NOT HAVE TO SPEND ONE NIGHT ON THE STREETS ALONE WHERE SHE COULD HAVE BEEN HARMED. HEALTHY, SMART, OBEDIENT, AND ENERGETIC CINNABON IS APPROXIMATELY 6 MONTHS OLD THEREFORE STILL A YOUNG VIBRANT PUPPY. NOT SPAYED SHE IS UP TP DATE ON VACCINATIONS AND IS NOT MICROCHIPPED. SUCH AN ANGEL, SHE IS ALWAYS READY TO PLEASE HER HUMAN. CRATE TRAINED, HOUSE BROKEN, LEASH TRAINED, AND IS ALMOST OBEYING THE "SIT" COMMAND CINNABON WILL NEED SOMEONE WITH TIME TO DEVOTE TO HER TRAINING AS SHE IS A PUP. FURTHERMORE, SHE WILL NEED PATIENCE AS SHE WILL NOT INITIALLY TRUST A NEW HUMAN BUT WARMS UP VERY QUICKLY! CINNABON IS CONTENT WITH SITTING NEXT TO YOU ON THE COUCH WHILE GIVING YOU KISSES AS HER WAY OF THANKING YOU FOR LOVING HER. THIS GIRL IS GOING TO MAKE SOMEONE'S FAMILY VERY HAPPY FOR MANY YEARS TO COME.

Mia was found as a stray running around a rural area and never reclaimed.  We were told it looked as though she had had puppies recently but none were ever found.  Mia is a really sweet girl and doing well in her foster home.  She loves people and is great with the older children she has been around. We assume she  probably had never been around other dogs  prior to coming to the rescue and with guidance will learn limits.   Mia is about year old and 40lbs.  She is potty and crate trained, does well on a leash. This girl is so cute with her short legs and little boots.    Our Mia would love nothing better than to have a best friend(s) that would love her as much as she would them.  If you are looking for a cute, happy, lovable new mate,  look no further than our sweet girl Mia!

animal.description:
Please read the dog's entire bio before you apply.  Sadly, we are no longer able to respond to every application, but will contact the one that is a good match within 3 days.
Ramon is a little chihuahua mix born around 7/2006.  This little man has a sad story and we are hoping for a happy ending for him, even if its not for long.    Ramon is all of 7 lbs with very long legs.   Ramon's owner decided that she could not care for him because of her pregnancy, we are not here to judge but its pretty sad.   Ramon is sweet, calm and pretty easy to get along with.  His labwork shows that he is in early stages of kidney failure, has a severe heart murmur and bad dental disease (unfortunately because of his heart and kidneys he is not an anesthesia candidate).   So, we are looking for someone special to provide a forever home for Ramon, even though it likely wont be for long considering his health.  He will need special food.  We do have a foster for him in the meantime, but a forever place would be even better.   Ramon likes to play with toys, enjoys other small dogs and is sweet with everyone he meets, what a nice little man.
Most of our dogs are not available to an out of the area adoption because of difficulty to follow up.  If you do not live within a 2 hr drive of Orange County, please email us before applying to see if the dog you are interested is may be a candidate for long distance adoption.    We only make consider long distance adoptions for dogs who have been in our rescue for 6 plus months with no local candidates.
If you are interested in adopting one of our rescues, please visit our main website for adoption procedures at www.pupsandpals.net and then fill out our application.  Please note that we are all volunteers so it may take up to 3 days to process your application, but you will hear back from us if your application is a good match for the pet. 
We do not have a shelter so individual appointments must be made to meet the pet you are interested in.  Our pets are fostered/boarded all over LA and Orange County.  
This pet is altered, vaccinated and has had a brief temperament evaluation to help us determine what type of  a home he/she would thrive in.  Please note that we put lots of time and effort to make sure our pets are ready to be someone's perfect pet before they go home.... and to make sure that we will have the best possible match for this pet we do require an : application, interview, adoption fee and in some case a home check.  
Listed for adoption: 1/13/2021
Adoption fee:  To be discussed, we just want to make sure that whoever adopts him his the means to continue his special diet and vet visits if needed.
PLEASE DO NOT call or email to see if a pet is available.  We update our pages daily so if he/she is pictured here in the available dogs section, we are accepting applications at this time.

animal.description:
Alligator, "Allie" as she is lovingly called by PetFriends Staff, is a large Shepherd cross with a friendly personality. She gets her name from the chomping sound she makes when she gets very excited. Allie weighs about 70 pounds and is about two years old.  She was found running down a highly trafficked street. She is extremely loving and wants nothing but pets and attention. 

Pet Friends' staff will socialize with her and give her some leash training.  Allie's high energy will need to be channeled through regular exercise and playtime with her owners.

If you're interested in large breed dogs and are an exercise enthusiast, Allie might be the dog you're looking for.  Call our office for a meet and greet if you are interested in Allie.  Your application will be sent for approval after you have met Allie.  

Our office number is (831) 634-1191.  We are located in Hollister CA, about 100 miles south of San Francisco.  Sorry, we do not ship our animals.  See all our animals on our website http://www.petfriends.org.

Phoenix is a 4 1/2 lb 3 yr old male Chihuahua. River is a 6 lb 6 yr old female Chihuahua. We believe River is mom. This duo is COMPLETELY bonded and will not be separated. They were surrendered by an owner that kept them in the backyard without attention or enough food. They are both still working on gaining some weight. The owner only had them about 4 months -- we do not have any history prior to. River is quite social and very affectionate. Phoenix is a bit timid and takes him longer to trust. Both are so adorable and incredibly gentle. Neither are barkers -- River does bark at and chase cats. This duo is now pad trained and doing great with going outside to potty thru the dog door. Their ideal home will have the human/s home more than not. No cats. Any other dogs in the home will need to be very gentle. These 2 are incredibly affectionate and love to sleep with their foster mom at night.
If you are interested in this duo please fill out an adoption application at www.casadeloveanimalrescue.org

Please note: Due to the high volume of individual inquiries, we may not be able to answer each message. 

Each furry friend is available until otherwise listed. 

If you would like to be considered, please apply at www.wsrh.com. If you have a specific question that is not covered in the profile, please send us a message. 

Clara grew up in a home with way too many dogs and is now learning how to appreciate the company of people. She absolutely loves to be held and cuddled but sometimes hides until she is reminded how much she likes it. Clara is fearful when she first meets and would prefer a quiet home with one or two adults and not a lot of social functions. Her ideal home would be with someone who would take her for short daily runs and has a backyard to explore. She is small, not even 8 lbs, so you won’t have to run far to meet her exercise needs.

Clara has been spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, and had her teeth cleaned. Her adoption donation is $350 which includes 6 months heartworm preventative meds, free microchip registration, and a safety harness.

If you are interested in adopting Clara, please review the adoption process and fill out the application on our website: http://wsrh.com

All dogs are available until “Adoption Pending” is noted next to their names. WSRH DOES NOT HAVE A PUBLIC SHELTER. ALL OF OUR DOGS ARE FOSTERED IN PRIVATE HOMES. Approved adopters only will be invited to meet the dogs.

Their adoption fee will include their spaying or neutering , their 3 series of their puppy shots, their rabies shot, their canine combo H3N2 and H3N8 vaccination , a free 30 day health insurance policy, 2 free bags of puppy food, a coupon booklet from Petsmart with great money saving coupons fir your puppy supplies, a free day at doggie day camp, a free hotel night stay, a 30 minute free dog training consultation , 2 free months of flea and tick prevention, a bag of dental dog bones , microchip , from Kennelwood they will be allowed one free day at doggie day camp, one free night hotel stay , and a free dog bath and grooming   Kennelwood has 8 Missouri locations and 2 Illinois locations.  You also can get one free vet exam and a free decal exam worth $62.00 at Webster Groves Animal Hospital within 2 weeks of your adoption date. They are extremely sweet and loving.  The female weighed 26 pounds on 1-4-2021 when we got her spayed:  you can call the shelter at 636-388-1636  or the landline number is 636-629-8781.  Ask for Ken if you want To come out and meet them.  You must call to schedule a meet and greet.  We will ask for people to wear a mask when coming inside to keep everybody safe.

animal.description:
**Please read Sugar Mama's entire profile, which includes a link to the adoption application. Thank you!** 

Meet Sugar Mama, a 2-year old, 75-pound Labrador/ American Bulldog mix young lady.

In an all too common story, Sugar Mama's parents have decided to divorce and neither feels they can take her into their new situation, leaving her homeless.

Sugar Mama is a sweetheart. Because she spent her whole life with one family where she knew nothing but love, so she is full of love herself. 

Sugar loves people and kids, gets along great with other dogs. She does make exceptions for cats, however.  She didn’t grow up with them and doesn’t want to include them in her friendship circle. 

Sugar loves her treats and would benefit for a home where she gets regular exercise as she is a bit chunky. 

Sugar cant wait to find her forever home where she can lay her doggie bed down, gets lots of attention and love

All dogs are up to date on vaccinations and spayed/neutered at the time of adoption.  All dogs require professional training to become the best family member they can be.

To adopt or learn more about Sugar Mama*, you must fill out an adoption application. To find the application, copy and paste this URL into your browser: WWW.GDRNE.COM/ADOPTION-APPLICATION [Adoption Fee: $495]  **  PLEASE READ: If a dog is listed, then s/he is currently available for adoption. Their information is correct to the best of our abilities and the information we have been given as of the day of posting. Please note, GDRNE does not guarantee the breed of any dog or puppy unless stated that we have run DNA. All breeds listed are educated estimates. Our dogs are rescued from various situations. It is most likely that both their parents were strays and even if not, mixes of some sort and that their grandparents were mixes as well. The dog may have some genetic material of an American Staffordshire Terrier (pit bull). The dogs are usually mixes of many breeds, making them a breed all their own - a True and adorable American MUTT. If you are interested in this dog, you must submit an application. Great Dog is not a shelter so there is no building you can visit. Our dogs live in private foster homes until adopted. To learn more about our *shelterless* rescue, adoption fees, and procedures, review the list of Frequently Asked Questions on our website at WWW.GDRNE.COM.

SNICKERS  is a sweetie seeking her forever family! 

This affectionate girl would love to be chilling next to you with her head on your lap. And then curl up on her dog bed for a nice long nap. She loves her naps! She has a mellow, laid back personality. But she also enjoys playtime, especially playing with squeaky balls. Throw the ball to her and watch her catch it mid-air. This girl has got skills! 

She’s house trained and crate trained. She is great with kids. She walks nicely beside you on a leash though sometimes she gets excited and jumps around when she sees other dogs. She’s working on that! Snickers doesn’t do well with other dogs in the home because she gets possessive of “her” humans. So she must be an only dog. It’s not known how she is around cats though a test can be arranged.

Snickers and her foster mom have worked together with a professional trainer ton basic obedience and those tips of the trade will be passed along to the adopter.  

We believe SNICKERS to be a HOUND/SHIP mix. Her estimated DOB is 10/12/2019, and she weighs 41 pounds.

For more information on our adoption process, please visit our website at www.youluckydogrescue.org and read our Adoption FAQ's and Before You Adopt documents. You can complete an online adoption application from our website. You can also email info@youluckydogrescue.org for additional details that are not included in this biography.

PRIVATE MEET & GREETS: Submitting an adoption application is required before a private meet & greet will be scheduled. We will complete a pre-screening first to make sure that the dog you are interested in is a good fit for you. That way, we don't unnecessarily waste your time or the foster's time. 

Our adoption fee is $300 and includes all age appropriate vaccines, spay or neuter and microchipping. All of our rescue dogs are heart worm tested annually beginning at 9 months of age, and they are kept on monthly heart worm and flea preventatives.

The breed and age included in this listing is based upon the opinion of a vet that has examined the dog. We cannot confirm the age of the dog unless the dog was born in the care of the rescue. 

We are located in the metro Atlanta area. We currently do not allow out of state adoptions as a home check is required as part of the adoption process.

animal.description:
Rock on with Rocky! Rocky is an awesome dog, with a charming, happy personality to match his handsome looks. Rocky has a little fan club among volunteers and is regularly described as happy-go-lucky, friendly and easy-going. This is in spite of seeing some hardship in his life - he arrived at the kennel heartworm positive, and with a badly broken tail that unfortunately had to be amputated. Despite this, Rocky seems to have an upbeat outlook on life and is looking to be someone's best buddy! He has a playful, silly spirit and a big affectionate side; given the chance, he will drape himself over your lap for pets and cuddles. Since he is heartworm positive, Rocky will require treatment. The cost is covered by Friends of City Dogs Cleveland, Rocky just needs to find a home where he can rest and recover for a while before getting back to normal fun dog stuff! Rocky is around 4 years old and weighs close to 50 lbs. Visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to set up a meet with Rocky and find out more about him!
Due to COVID-19, CITY DOGS is currently doing adoptions by APPOINTMENT ONLY. Please visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to request a meet and greet! 

Questions? Email: citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us | Call: (216) 664-3476
Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

Hours:
10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.

Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. You must schedule a meet with a dog in advance - we are not currently accepting walk-ins. Please look online first to see if there are any dogs you think would be a good fit for your home before scheduling a meet. To get the process started, visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog and fill out the form. One of our adoption counselors will get in touch to schedule and confirm your meet! At the kennel, an adoption counselor will introduce you and your family to the adoptable dogs, share information we know about them, and discuss our suggested ways for successfully integrating a new dog into your home. You are welcome to meet multiple dogs. If the dog you adopt is already fixed, he or she may leave with you that day - otherwise, the dog can go home after receiving the spay or neuter surgery.)

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog once they are in the home. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.

Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DAPPL, Rabies, and Bordatella vaccines, though you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.?

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.4 Lucky Dogs has no facility in which to view dogs. All of our dogs are in loving fosters homes throughout West Central Florida. To be considered, please apply for our dogs at www.4luckydogs.org. As a general rule we do not adopt outside of the state of Florida unless the person/family is known to our rescue.
It's time to find Willow her forever home. She has some home requirements so please read before proceeding. Willow came to us as if she had never seen a human before. It was obvious her experience with people was not positive. She is timid and afraid of almost everything. A month later and she allows her foster mom to touch her and has even wandered over to initiate touch. This is a huge improvement for her.
Her new home will need to be extremely patient with her. Allow her to adjust and decompress. This could take months possibly.
She requires a fenced yard. This is for her safety. If she were to escape, she will RUN and as scared as she is of everything, it would be hard to catch her, and she would put herself in grave danger.
She requires another dog or two in the home. Preferably a confident medium to larger size. She has been initiating play especially in the morning. (Shes an early riser.)
She enjoys her crate. She feels comfortable in it. Currently the door is left open so she can retreat if needed. However, she will spend ALL day in it if allowed. She has also presented with some resource guarding of it when her foster siblings got too close and growled. It is important to help her engage in life outside the crate.
She is very treat and food motivated. Has been known to counter surf to get to those bag of treats you may have left laying around.
She sneaks toys. She seems to like the antlers and is so cute watching her chew on them. It's likely she never had anything like that before.
She appears to be housetrained and has not had an accident since the first couple of days in her foster home. Most likely she learned this from her foster siblings. She has full run of the house at night and when her fister mom is home. She does go in her crate when her foster mom isn't home but again, it's for her safety as it's unknown what she may try and get into when not being supervised.
No little kids. Fast movements frighten her, loud noises frighten her, too much going on at one frightens her. Also small toys could easily get destroyed or consumed resulting in major problems.
She is not leash trained. The outside world is terrifying for her which is why the fenced yard is required. She will bolt if given the opportunity and a double leash would be recommended when leaving the home if she must. Dog parks and outdoor venues are not recommended for her. (At least not at this time.)
She does love attention. Although nervous, she has never attempted to bite or snap at anyone. As your hand goes closer and closer, you can see the fear, however, once the ear scratches and rub down begins, she relaxes and seems to enjoy it. Her foster mom has also placed her on the sofa with her and immersed her in pets and she fell asleep on her lap.
Again...slow is key.
She is a great girl and in time will make a perfect companion. Even one month in she is a different dog. It's important to get her to her new home so she can acclimate to the change. She has been an easy dog to foster. Willow's adoption fee is $400 and she comes spayed and microchipped and fully vaccinated for a year.

animal.description: Hello, everyone!  My name is Jackie (HWTH#21020A).  I am a Siberian Husky mix, born 1/20/20 and I weigh 37 lbs.  I was found by a good Samaritan in Palmdale.  My owners never came to get me so I was relinquished to Halfway to Home to find my forever family.  I am a friendly, energetic girl who hopes to find owners who enjoy an active lifestyle.  I like going for long walks, and other outdoor activities such as hiking and camping would be right up my alley!  I need a big yard with a tall fence to run and play when we aren't out on our adventures, so I would not be a good fit for an apartment or condo.   Obedience training is important so that I learn what is expected of me, and it will help me bond with you.  I have not spent much time around other dogs or children, but I am a playful girl so I would probably enjoy having one or both as playmates to keep me entertained.  Cats are also an unknown for me, but cats and Huskies are generally not a good match.  Huskies do shed, so regular brushing will keep my coat shiny and clean. More than anything else, I want to be treated as a member of the family, and in return I think you will find me to be a loyal and loving companion.  If you would like more information about me, or would like to make an appointment to meet me, please call Sandy at tele# 661-824-4495 (this is a landline phone).  Thank you for taking the time to read about me, and I hope to meet you soon!

animal.description: Huxley is a 6 year old blue male currently being fostered in Grand Rapids Michigan. Hux is one of 27 dogs seized from a home in Northern Michigan in November 2020. animal.description:
{s3829code380/}
If you would like to provide this dog a loving home, please fill out a pre-adoption application.

Have a question? Please read our Frequently Asked Questions and Adoption Processed Explained documentation.
_________ B I O ______________

Name: Tyke
Size: ~Large range: 61-100 lbs
Adoption Donation:$250 (applicable sales tax included).Adoption fees may be paid by cash or check.
Other:Neutered Male, Vaccinations current, Microchip, Older considerate children only, Not Apartment-friendly, NO Cats, NO Small Dogs

Tyke is such a ham! You're going to love him!

Foster Home Feedback

*
NO Cats; NO Small dogs

*
Older considerate children only

*
Tyke needs to go to a home with another large-sized dog - he needs a dog buddy his size to help him feel comfortable and confident!

1/13/21: If you have been thinking that there is too much extra space on your couch, Tyke is the dog for you! He can be skeptical of new people at first (and is selective about men), but once he warms up, he loves being around his people! If you are thinking about adopting Tyke, know that it takes him a couple of weeks to start to settle in, and he needs slow introductions to new people. If your home is a busy place with lots of people coming and going, Tyke isn't the dog for you. He also seems to do best on a fairly predictable schedule. The good news is he loves his kennel, and he often goes there voluntarily to get some alone time.

This sweet boy has had quite the journey over his 9 months with me. In August and September, we went through a positive reinforcement training program to work on his reactivity (using a clicker and lots of treats) and we have continued to use this training to help Tyke. We hope his new home will be willing to continue this work. Tyke is very treat-motivated, so he enjoys practicing with the clicker!

In November, Tyke had surgery on his knee, his recovery went really well.
We have been working on taking longer walks to keep building up his strength, and he does love going on walks of about a mile. He has also loved being able to play in the snow. Tyke has done really well living in an apartment, but I think he would love having a backyard to play in.

Adopting Tyke will require patience and a commitment to keep working with him, but the reward is great! He is such a loving boy and has been working hard to get ready for his new home.

6/12/2020: Tyke spent a few days in another home and he struggled to adjust to the new noises and the new people. He doesn't like surprises! If you are interested in adopting Tyke, know that it will take some time for him to settle in. If you are in an apartment where noise is an issue and you need to be conscientious of your neighbors, Tyke may not be a good fit.

When he first came to stay with me, every new voice that he heard outside my apartment got him up and moving (and barking). Now that Tyke has settled in, he is so calm. There have been many apartment showings in my building over the past week, and even though we can hear the voices of people coming in and out, Tyke is content to just relax and listen. The only time he has barked recently is if I am trying to sleep in and he wants his breakfast. He likes his food and his treats!

Tyke is doing better and better with new people. I took him to the lake with my parents and he went right up to them right away with no growling. He loved the long car ride out and back, and all the hiking that we were able to do.

I have learned so much about Tyke over the past month - he is really a special guy and is looking for a forever home!

5/21/2020: I have had Tyke for almost two weeks now and he has been a fantastic addition to my home. If you are looking for a snuggle buddy, Tyke is your guy!

He does pretty well on his leash, but he is easily distracted by all the fun things to smell. Tyke handles running into other dogs really well - he is able to calmly walk by them even if they are barking. He has gotten many comments on how well behaved he is.

I haven't tested him out with other people beyond the people we meet on our walks. He can (rarely) growl and lunge when new people approach him, and he will hide behind me if there is a large group. Tyke is the friendliest dog once he warms up to you, but it may take some time. I would recommend that he not go to a home with younger children as he can lunge when he is startled and he doesn't always realize his strength. I hope that Tyke can go to a home that can make him feel comfortable and safe, and that will have the patience for his quirks!

Tyke is potty trained and crate trained. I leave him out at night and he sleeps quietly (aside from occasional, adorable snoring) on his bed.

4/22/2020: Tyke is such a sweetheart, who's favorite things to do are going for walks and cuddling with his humans. Once we get back from a walk he will jump up on the couch and nap until he's ready to go again!

We have had absolutely no accidents and he hardly ever barks! The only time we've heard Tyke bark is when he meets men, so slow introductions would be best with new people (especially guys). Once he realizes that they will give him lots of pets, he loves them and warms up quickly. He would do best in a home where there isn't a lot of people coming and going. He also loves the company of other dogs and would love to have a dog buddy to show him that people are not scary. Tyke is an awesome dog who just wants lots of love!

4/10/2020 Volunteer Feedback: Tyke just came to the rescue today, and I've spent a bit of time today getting to know him. He is a super sweet boy; very well mannered, affectionate, and kind of goofy! He knows how to sit, although he is very treat motivated so he can't sit still for too long before he starts getting wiggly because he wants the treat! He met both of my dogs and did great with them. He likes to play but is also content just to follow them around. I took Tyke and my two dogs for a walk - he is great on a leash! He sometimes pulled a bit if he really wanted to sniff something, but he by no means was dragging me around.

Tyke seems kennel trained and potty trained. I met him at our facility early this morning and hung out with him for a bit. I left for about 4 hours and came back. He went into his kennel fine when I left, and it was clean when I got back. I had put a blanket and some bones in his kennel and when I returned, the blanket was still intact and it appeared he had kept busy chewing on the bone! He waited to do his business once we got outside. We are still getting to know this handsome fella, and will hopefully get him into a foster home soon to learn more about him. Check back for more feedback soon!To view additional dogs available for adoption, please see our website: www.4luvofdog.org 2/2/21 1:34 PM

animal.description:
**This dog has a bite record-- Please read below thoroughly before applying!**

Calli was thrown from a truck on a freeway, and immediately afterward was clipped by oncoming traffic. A good samaritan stopped to try to catch her, and once he did he rushed her to an emergency vet where luckily they found she just had superficial scrapes and a bruised lung which would heal on it’s own. Calli's all healed now, and is ready for adoption! 

Calli’s background is a mystery, but the vet confirmed she’s about a year old, 42-ish lbs (she should be around 45-46 lbs once she puts on more weight). She’s timid at first with new people, but warms up quickly (especially with women) and easily becomes a velcro, cuddly, dog. She’s young and energetic, and would benefit from a family that can give her a good amount of exercise and basic obedience training.

She needs slow introductions to new dogs, and can be defensive (gives warnings by showing her teeth) if cornered by a pushy unfamiliar dog. If she’s in a home with other dogs, she should be separated at meal times and when she has something high-value. She has gotten into tussles and a fight with her previous foster sibling over chews, and her foster mom was bitten and scratched up in the process of breaking up the fight-- no puncture from the bite, but it did break skin and warranted her label as having a 'bite history'. In her new foster home, she has had zero incidences with the resident dog and humans.

Calli is not kid-tested. She is OK with dog-friendly cats but should be supervised at all times around cats, because she does try to play with them. She will need obedience training and structure in her new home to make sure she matures into a great canine citizen. So far she’s good in her crate overnight and between walks, knows 'place', sit, and 'wait', and is working on her loose leash walking and recall. On walks she only reacts to other dogs if they bark at her, but it's easy to get her attention back on her handler. 

If you want to give this sweet girl a second chance at life, apply at harasf.org/application!

animal.description:
Oh, Louie. If you are looking for a roly, poly, opinionated ball of fur - Look no further! Louie is your main man.  All 27 pounds of him.  He is a chihuahua mix, about 8 years young. Louie came to us very sick, but recovered quickly and is doing well. He is a bit of a spit fire, and likes to keep his world small. He enjoys short walks, and sitting outside if it isn’t too cold for short amounts of time. Believe it or not, he can run - but it reminds us of the cutest waddling duck you could ever find. He likes comfy beds, and is learning about toys. He enjoys stuffed toys, and will chase them a little bit while grunting and growling playfully like a little piggie. Louie does like to beg his foster mom for food, though we are working on convincing him to take a more active role in the lifestyle change we have bestowed upon him.  He is looking for a calm home, without small children. Louie takes some time to warm up to new people, and can be easily startled. He is looking for a patient home to help him continue to build his confidence, and help him feel safe. While he may disagree, we are also looking for a home who will be committed to helping him work towards a healthier future with a diet and exercise plan. Louie has lived with other dogs his entire life, however he is not a big fan of sharing attention, food, or toys with them and may do best living out his golden years as the only dog in the household. Given Louie’s nervousness with new people, we would also be open to a foster to adoption home for him, where he would remain in our foster program for a few weeks while our trainers provide any support needed to ensure a smooth transition. We know he may be looking for just the right home, but trust us - he is worth it!  He is snuggly, sweet, and can we say adorable!!! 
The adoption donation for Louie is $100.  This donation helps to cover veterinary expenses including spay/neuter, microchip and vaccinations.

Wish Upon a Rescue is a 501(c)3 non-profit, foster based animal rescue. If you would like to meet	Louie, please complete our adoption questionnaire at www.wishuponarescue.org/adopt. We will review your responses and be in contact to schedule a meet and greet at a time and place convenient for your family and our team members.

BIO:
Let's play! My name is Rylee and I am a silly and sweet young gal who is available for adoption through Fetching Tails Foundation. I am a typical young energetic puppy with a lot of growing to do and need adopters who are committed to working with me on training, including my potty skills. I love playing with all the toys I can get my pretty paws on and hanging out with my people, and would love to hang out with you! My ears are as big as my head, and I cannot wait to hear you say that I am your Rylee-girl for life!

*Have the knowledge and agreement of all adults living in the household

*Have a valid ID with current address (please provide proof of address if ID address is not up-to-date)
*Be approved as a suitable adoptive home by Fetching Tails Foundation

If interested please fill out an application on our website at www.fetchingtailsfoundation.org; please make sure you fill in every required field/question or your submission will not go through. Please note that we take time to learn as much as we can about each dog in our care and our bios are our current observations; we are unable to make any guarantees on the future health or temperament of your adopted dog. Most dogs in our care come with unknown pre-rescue history and as such breed and age estimates are an educated guess.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Please review our Adoption Process before filling out an application. If you would like to try a Foster to Adopt trial, please fill out an Adoption Application.

If you are only interested in temporarily Fostering one of our rescues, please fill out a Foster Application.

Meet Marley (fka Eddie)!Marley (fka Eddie) was adopted from ARWOB in October 2019. Sadly he needs to be relinquished back to ARWOB. We received detailed information from his previous adopter about some of his challenges and as such, we are looking for the RIGHT match for Marley. Therefore, please read his biography thoroughly and if you believe he would be a good match, you are welcome to consider a foster-to-adopt trial before finalizing his adoption.NOTE: We are looking for the right temporary foster home for him ASAP and would love to have him situated as soon as 1/20/21. All foster supplies are provided by ARWOB. His previous owner was not interested in crate training, but he was crate trained when in foster care with ARWOB in 2019. We can provide his new foster family with a crate for him, but we do know he is house trained and does not necessarily need a crate. It would be up to the new foster if they would like to use one. Marley will need to be in a home with NO dogs. If the home has cats, he must be supervised when around them and not left alone as a precaution. Marley's development with his previous owner is not clear, but we believe there was a lack of leadership and training. Unfortunately, his previous owner also became physically unable to handle a large breed dog. We are waiting for more information about Marley and have requested videos, but as a foster you will have access to a behaviorist to work with Marley. This would require the foster to drive to Carmel Valley likely once a month to meet with the trainer and/or do Zoom meetings for ongoing sessions. Marley will need to work on his leash walking/reactivity and quickly corrected when he comes into the presence of other dogs. If you have any additional questions, please email us at animalrescuers@sbcglobal.net. However, the first step in the process would be to submit an online application through our website. If you would like to ONLY foster Marley, please complete an online foster application. If you are interested in foster-to-adopt or adopting immediately, please complete an online adoption application. These applications can be found at: https://www.arwob.org/forms/ORIGINAL RESCUE STORY:Meet adorable Eddie! First thing that comes to mind when you meet Eddie is Teddie Bear! He is a large boy with a big heart. He was pulled from a high kill shelter in Ensenada just as he was ready to be euthanized. He was fostered by his rescuer in Ensenada for a month. She has 2 dogs his size and he did well with them. She would also take him to work and he would hang out in her cubicle and he did great. He is not a big leash puller and tends to walk next to you. We do not know how he will be around with cats. He is a great dog and he has been learning to play fetch with a tennis ball and frisbee. animal.description:
Hi there everybody! My name is Zeus! I’m 8 months old, about thirty pounds, and I am just learning what it means to be a pup. When I hear ‘good boy’ I get so excited I can hardly control my wiggly zoomy body!!! It’s so fun to learn new things! 
I had a bit of a rough start down south, but since I moved to Wisconsin I’ve learned that I love the snow, I love to play, and I LOVE to cuddle. If I could be attached to my foster mom all the time, life would be perfect. 
I’m still learning how to walk calmly on a leash and how to greet new friends without being too excited. Don’t worry though, I know lots of good stuff! I potty outside, I know how how to sleep quietly in my crate when you leave, I can spin, sit, lay down, shake, come, wait, and I’m pretty sure I know what ‘off’ means sometimes....
I think new people are a bit scary, and I would do better in a house that doesn’t have lots of friends over all the time. Once we are friends though, man do I adore you. I love other dogs, but low-energy dogs might not be a big fan of all my jumping and running. I think I would love the energy of kids, but I get so excited and love to jump up and say hello- so smaller kiddos might not be a fan. 
Overall, I’m looking for a calm home where I can play play play and then snore around for a bit. I’d love to show you my tricks and learn some more, and I’d love to be allowed to sit with you on the couch and play with you in the snow. I will need lots of good structure, and a human who is willing to help me keep learning. Does this sound like you? If you think we could be Furever friends, let’s meet. I’m wiggly all over just thinking about it!
Zeus is fostering in Cudahy, WI.  To apply, please go to www.ruffluckdogrescue.com.

animal.description:
This sweet boy is Sterling.  He is a 2 year old German Shepherd mix who weighs 46 lbs but should be more like 65 lbs.  Sterling was found on the street extremely underweight.  He has gained a few pounds in his foster home but needs to gain a lot more weight. Despite being a stray who was hungry and lonely, he has fallen in love with his foster humans and their dogs immediately and have quickly picked up potty training and crate training.

Sterling is a big lovable goofball who has lots of energy. He plays hard and loves hard. Sterling loves to run and play chase with his foster dog brother.  He loves snuggling on the couch with you and would also love sleeping in your bed snuggled up next to you if you'll let him. He is loyal to and protective of his people and definitely wouldn't let any pesky squirrels sneak into your backyard.  

Because he was such a hungry boy,  he can be protective of his food and sometimes of toys.  Therefore, he likes to eat his food in the safety of his crate and chew his most favorite toys in his crate.  The first couple of days he would defend his belongings from the other dogs and his foster parents but with a little bit of reassurance and trading he no longer guards his things.  

In his forever home, Sterling will need another very playful dog and a fenced yard.  He will need a 6ft fence as he would easily jump a shorter fence.  Because of his resource guarding, we would prefer he be in a home with older kids (16 and up).  

Sterling is leash trained, crate trained, mostly house trained if taken out every hour for right now.  HIs foster mom says he walks perfect on a leash and doesn't pull or drag her along. He sleeps well all night long in his crate, but come 6:00 AM he is ready for breakfast. 

Sterling is neutered, microchipped, and current on his vaccines.  His adoption fee is $175.

If you would like to adopt Sterling and make him a part of your family, please apply at FYDRadopt.com!

animal.description:
Geraldine is a 10-12 year old, 62 pound purebred lab that was turned into a shelter after she was found wandering down the road. When no one came to claim her, we took her and she went right to a wonderful foster home where we have been able to address several issues.

Her x-rays show that she has a bad hip and arthritis in her other legs. We have her on pain meds, which has greatly helped her mobility, but she still needs a little help sometimes. She also has heartworms, which makes her breathing a little labored at times. We have an easy heartworm protocol and she should do fine with it. She also had some head tremors when she came in and had a seizure a couple of weeks ago, but meds seem to have stopped that. Geraldine has a myriad of issues, but she has made herself at home with the foster and all of her dogs. She seems to really enjoy her time with the foster and will sometimes bark softly at her when she wants some company. She is a total sweetheart and we would love to find a quiet home for her where she can get caught up on all of the love and attention that she seems to have missed in her life. Were not sure how long she has got, but we will keep her as a foster and cover the vetting if someone will just LOVE her. If you have a quiet home and would like to help this deserving girl, please email info@atlantalabrescue.com.

animal.description:
If you're looking for a running, hiking, go everywhere with you kind of dog, then you may have met your match. Molly is a great dog, loves people, good with dogs and cats. On walks she'll tend to want to say hi to everyone - whether they welcome it or not. :-) She's bigger than a Blue Heeler, but smaller than a Great Pyranees, with a soft wavy coat and alert brown eyes

Molly's idea home will have 1 or 2 adults with dog experience - herding dog experience preferred. Backyard required - Molly loves to play fetch, chase squirrels and sniff the wind.

 

If you are reading this, we are still accepting applications on this pet. 

Our Adoption Process:


	Meet the Adoption Criteria. Before you do anything else, make sure you meet our adoption criteria. You must be at least 21 years old. You must live within a 60-mile radius of Richardson, Texas. You must share veterinary records for all pets currently in your home and all pets owned in the last five years. All pets in the home must be spayed or neutered. If you rent your home, you must provide verification that pets are allowed on the property. You must be willing to be interviewed by an adoption counselor and you must undergo an in person or virtual home visit from an RHS representative.
	Complete Application. https://www.richardsonhumanesociety.org/adopt/
	Phone Interview. Compatible applicants will be forwarded to a counselor who will contact the applicant for a phone interview.
	Home Visit. If all the steps above are completed satisfactorily, we will set up a visit where you can meet the pet you are interested in. We will try to include the foster parent so you can learn more about how the pet is in a home environment.
	Complete Adoption. If all feel it is a good match, we will schedule the adoption at your home or an off-site location. The applicant will need to complete the adoption contract and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fee is $250 for adult dogs, $300 for puppies (under 1 year) and $125 for cats. Discounts are available for senior-aged pets.

animal.description:
1220606 - Hi! My name is Ferris and Im a very special little guy looking for a very special family. Im a 10 months old and 12 pounds chiweenie mix from Texas.

When I first arrived to my foster home I was very territorial. I finally started relaxing after a week there. I specially enjoy being around my foster mom and dad, their kids stress me out because they are kind of loud so I would definitely do best in a house without kids. I love their dog (a super friendly male Russell terrier mix), hes my best friend and we play together all the time! But I can be mean the other dog (a little Chihuahua puppy) even though we were together at the shelter, and I'm not a fan of the cat. Im getting a lot better at hanging out with all of them, though. Socializing has certainly helped me improve my behavior, but I amy be best as an only dog or at least I shouldn't be with dogs smaller than me.

I am very sweet when I feel safe and relaxed. I love to cuddle and give kisses. Im an active puppy so I love to chew on my toys, play and go on walks. Im getting really good at walking on the leash!

Im almost fully potty trained and as long as yiu take me out every 4 hours during the day I have no accidents in the house. 

Im looking for a forever family who has the time and kind heart to keep training me. Itd be easier for me to adapt to a family with no kids, no other dogs and no cats. I like to have all the attention! But I also need someone who can teach me to socialize little by little. Itd be really helpful if my new family could take me to a Puppy Training. Im really smart and willing to learn good manners, I just need love and patience to be able to do it!

If youd like to meet me and are ready to have me in your family for the next 15 years or so, please fill an application at www.sloppykisses.org/adoptions! Ill give you my unconditional love and company in return.

Haskell

Arrives in the NE/CO/WY area 1/17/21

Bull Terrier mix

9 months old

SUPER dog friendly

Cats unknown 

Loves kids with dog manners

Hearing impaired

House trained

Crate trained and we will start to work with him on signs 

Fully vetted

32lbs

Haskell is a 10 month old Bull Terrier mix from the RGV. He happens to also be deaf. Knowing he was shelter bound I'm his owner reached out for help. The situation was super sad being that Haskell also lost his brother and littermate to a inoperable tumor. His owner, a young mom of a young child, was facing losing her home if he didn't leave as the landlord changed his mind on having pets. A mutual friend posted his story and we watched to see if any would take. Unfortunately with Bull Terriers being frequently surrendered most breed specific rescues can't afford to take mixes. His future wasn't looking very bright and knowing he was deaf he wouldn't likely make it out of a shelter situation. He has an amazing foster who reached out and offered to help so we stepped up and he arrived to her Monday. He was fully vetted yesteday and it was confirmed he was deaf. He is doing awesome with his 6 foster siblings and we will be working on teaching him signs so that he has the best chance of success in the future. 

We would really like Haskell to go to a home with Bull Terrier experience as well as hearing impaired experience. We realize this may be hard to find so we are hoping to at least find someone with experience with hearing impaired dogs. 

 $250.00 Adoption Fee 

(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.)

To Contact Us

Message us through our website http://www.highplainspaw.org

Message the Facebook Page at https://www.facebook.com/HighPlainsPAW

Fill out our Adoption Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/adoption-application

Fill out our Foster Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/foster-application

Email us at highplainspaw@gmail.com

Call our VOICEMAIL at (402)957-1578

WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY ALL OUR DOGS ARE LOCATED IN FOSTER HOMES. This means there is no place for you to go in person to view our dogs. We ask that an application be filled out and we will go from there!

animal.description:
This is Claire, a beautiful 1-2 year old, 35lb, Springer Spaniel Mix. Claire came to Heartland very afraid and very broken. Somewhere in her past, she has been severely traumatized by unknown sources and because of this, she is very slow to trust her surroundings and the people handling her. Claire's potential adopter must understand that she still needs a lot of work, training and dedication to help her though this recovery period. 
Despite her traumatic past, Claire has shown her foster mom that with a large amount of patience, understanding and time, she is full of love and thoroughly enjoys being loved on once she has begun to trust you. It took roughly TWO MONTHS for her foster mom to gain her trust and start to see the darling dog Claire has the potential to be. She does well in a crate, she prefers it to being out at first. Claire currently does not do well in cars. She may urinate, defecate or vomit out of fear while in them. She is not comfortable with leashes and will need a dedicated human to gently train her to be leashed. The perfect forever home for Claire would be Local to northern Indiana to reduce travel anxiety, full of patience, have a calm and encouraging environment where she can learn to trust at her own pace without fear of negative reinforcement or stern punishment and her humans understand that this gentle girl needs A LOT of time to adjust and feel comfortable. She may not let you pet her until she trusts you but doesn't mind if you're nearby with some tasty treats! She does well with other gentle and playful dogs and will follow their lead. Claire would do best in a home with no small children or children that can be relatively relaxed and quiet while she is figuring out if she is safe or not. She needs a safe quiet place to retreat when afraid such as a covered crate, under a bed or her own room. Claire does require 2 medications daily for life for her anxiety costly roughly $65.00 a month. A yard with a physical fence is also a requirement at this time. If you think you have the dedication and heart to let this beautiful dog learn to love you, it will be worth the potentially long wait!

All dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations, heartworm tested negative (age 7 months and older) and microchipped. We do not ship or transport. A dog's adoption donation is $200. There is a $5 fee for credit/debit cards.

Dogs: No other male dogs

Flash is a sweet guy! He came to us quite terrified but he's is getting better with time.  We've noticed some quirks with this cutie. He does not like children, takes a few times being with a person before he will open up to them, and he's nervous while walking on a leash, so he needs a good collar and harness for walking. Due to the fear issues, we are requiring a physically fenced in yard for this gentleman. If you would like to meet him, please fill out an application today! Please note this guy is going to need you to come for at least three visits for him to feel comfortable. 

The Animal Rescue Project (www.animalrescueproject.org) is committed to the best possible veterinary care for the pets it rescues and it is looking for adopters who will be similarly committed.

All dogs and puppies are given a general check-up when they enter our program. They receive medication to remove any intestinal parasites (worms), fleas, and ticks they may have. Dogs greater than six months of age are checked for heartworm. If heartworm positive, the Animal Rescue Project treats the disease. Dogs and pups receive all age-appropriate vaccinations for distemper, and dogs greater than four months of age are also vaccinated for rabies, in compliance with State of Michigan laws. All dogs are also microchipped.

Most dogs and older puppies are spayed or neutered before adoption. In the case of puppies not old enough to be safely sterilized, a $50 deposit is required at the time of adoption and is refunded to the adopter with proof of sterilization.

The Animal Rescue Project requires every adopter to establish an active relationship with a veterinarian no later than 10 days after adoption. Adopters will receive a plan for routine veterinary care at the time of adoption and are expected to work with their vet to complete the plan.

animal.description:
Linus in search of a new home through no fault of his own.  His people split up and the parent he stayed with was irresponsible and did not take care of him. Linus is a beautiful boy who was born in March of 2018.  He is housetrained, gets along with other dogs,  and loves human attention.  He is unproven with cats, as the only cat he knew was an outside cat and did not enter his space. We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 6 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Linus will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $350

animal.description:
*****Belgian Malinois Adoption requirements*****

The dog you have selected is a Belgian Malinois.  This is a breed that has very specific needs for an adoptive home.  Because of their need for a high level of exercise, both mentally and physically and their need for ongoing training, only applicants with demonstrated owner/handler experience with this breed will be considered.  The vast majority of them are not best suited as family pets, but in homes with experienced handlers knowledgeable of their needs and breed characteristics.  We will not place in homes with small children or small dogs/cats.  

Meet beautiful Sarah!

Sarah loves playing with large dogs and enjoys chasing them. She is always happy and eager to please, but can also be a bit timid, submissive and a complete follower. Because she is so eager to please, she will learn very quickly. Sarah is about 3 years old.

Being a malinois, she would definitely benefit from other large dog(s) to keep her mind and body occupied, or lots of people activity, or she may resort to destructive behaviors if she's not mentally and physically challenged. Sarah is crate trained, as well, and loves playing with toys.

If you can give Sarah an indoor forever home, please fill out our online application on our website at http://www.savingpawsrescueaz.com/adoption-form/  

 We will only schedule meet and greets with an approved application. We are an all-volunteer organziation.  It may take a couple of days to process an application and complete reference checks.

Thank you for your interest in saving a life!

How are you doin? I am a tall, dark, and handsome pup looking to share a spot on the couch next to someone like you! My name is Bert and I am a fixed, 2 year old male and approximately 60lbs. I came into the Rescue with my littermates and was fortunately enough to follow my brother, Ernie, into my previous home and now and into my foster parents' care. 

But let's not dwell on the past! 

I am a fun loving, easy going guy who thoroughly enjoys taking up space on a couch. 

Feet cold? No issue. I'm actually a lap dog. Too big? No, never. Just think of me as a space heater! Full body pillow! Your best companion ever! I am super smart, house trained and crate trained.

If you doubt my border collie heritage, just ask  my sister! She had her DNA done and I am supposedly part dutch shepherd, border collie, lab and more! 

I currently reside on the North Eastern side of Dallas and am looking for an assertive dog savvy person willing to teach me some tricks! 

I take up some space, so apartment life is not ideal for me. I need a place to really streeeetttch my legs and play with some friends! 

My foster parents have not seen how I react with kids, but cats are no issue for me. 

I am curious about them and how they smell, but I am much more interested in where they eat their food! 

So how’s about it? Can you make room in your heart for a big oaf like me? Fill out an application today! 

BCRRT is a Texas based rescue with fosters in TX and OK. Our adoption areas are TX, OK and surrounding states. We do not allow shipping/transport of dogs to other states. If you are interested and would like to apply please visit: https://bcrrt.com/adoption/ and fill out an application form.

animal.description:
Meet RJ!

RJ is a very handsome, tall 4 year old red boy with natural ears who was surrendered to the rescue by his owner.

RJ is an absolute lovebug!  Snuggling is a pastime.  No matter how much room is available, he becomes a tiny little dog-nut.
Men need to be introduced but he quickly accepts them.  He flops on his foster dad as much as his foster mom. We have not had him around kids but his prior owner reports he is kid friendly as well.
He would love a dog more his size and age to roughhouse with, he is always ready for play and isn’t aggressive towards other dogs.

RJ lived with a kitty and 2 Chihuahuas previously, but the foster’s and neighbor’s outside cats are very INTERESTING and seem tasty.
He really tries to reach them and will circle back until the kitty is out of sight.

He is house trained and crate trained.

RJ does bark at things outside and likes to run window to window or room to room for a better look.
RJ needs toys, he loves nylabones and strong rubber balls.  He will do his best to catch anything thrown towards him and will fetch, but doesn’t understand if he drops it, you will throw it again.

RJ is a strong puller and needs someone with a STRONG arm. HE also requires good fencing.  The foster has 4 board wood fencing, but if the gap is enough he will try to go under.

If you have a good fence and no cats, RJ would be a great pup for you!

All of our dogs are in foster homes and are available to meet by appointment only and only after an application has been completed.  To complete an application, please visit our website at www.bluegrassdobermanrescue.org

Activity Level: Moderate. River is happy to snooze the day away on a couch or in a dog bed, but the moment you grab the leash, she's ready to go! She is accustomed to being in an enclosed yard during the day while her owners are at work and sleeping in a kennel at night.

Adults: River loves people and has never met a stranger. She likes to press herself against people's legs and wag her tail so hard her whole back end wiggles. She is well-mannered and never gets "mouthy" or jumps up, no matter how excited she may be. She also hardly ever barks - she prefers to snort, cuff, and chortle.

Children: River currently lives in a house with a baby and has spent time with toddlers. She is very patient with children and has never snapped or growled at them. If a child is rough or overly attentive, she moves away or (if the child is persistent) retreats to a different room.

Other Dogs: River does not tolerate other dogs well - I suspect due to bad experiences as a puppy or during her time on the streets. She would do best as the single dog in a household.

Cats: River has an active prey drive and views small animals as something to chase and catch. She would do best in a household without cats.

animal.description:
A GENTLE COMPANION AWAITS YOU:  9 years old / 55 lbs. and needs to gain a little more weight.

Hello, my name is Conner.  When I came to Mostly Mutts from animal control, I was in rough shape – very thin, with infected skin and fur loss - from long term neglect.  With great vet care and lots of love in my foster home, I have already gained over 10 lbs.  and my fur is coming back in.  I still have a way to go, though I am filling out and healing more each day – ready to meet my new family!    

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  There are two friendly dogs in my foster home who greeted me nicely when I arrived and – though I was initially scared, I have come out of my shell and get along famously with both now.  So, if you have a nice gentle doggie at home already, let’s meet / Cat’s unknown / I met kids once in my foster home, and I did enjoy them.  They were very sweet and gentle with me and I with them. I was especially fond of the little girl wanting to spend lots of time with her. They were 6 and 8 years old - so calm children this age or older could be a good fit in my new home, let’s meet and see!  

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  My foster describes me as the ‘epitome of a Velcro dog… but in a good way’.  I respond to love and kindness and want to be with my people.  I am a curious guy who always wants to know what my people are up to.  I even brave the vacuum cleaner to follow my foster mom as she vacuums.  She says it is as if I am watching over her.  I wait patiently as she goes up and down the stairs to let me outside.  So sweet!  I have such a kind nature; my foster says that whoever adopts me is going to be very happy.  How about that! / My energy level is 3-5.  

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY:  I am well-behaved, and I will come when my foster mom calls me.  She is working on other commands with me, and – since I take treats graciously and gently - I bet you can too / I don’t need a crate in my foster home, as my doggie bed is my safe place / I have good potty habits in my foster home – giving signals like pacing around and going to the door when I need a potty break.   I also understand the phrase ‘gotta go potty?”

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I enjoy being out in the yard with my people and like to explore and wander around (though I am always keeping my foster mom in sight) / I can’t think of any dislikes, though I need a few minutes to get used to new folks.  I have suffered from neglect in the past, so I would not be happy if I did not get the love, good care and attention all doggies deserve!

• MEDICAL:   I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and neutered.  I am continuing medicated baths 2/week to help my skin heal and my fur to continue to grow back in and these can be done in my new home. 

I am looking to add lots of love to my new home with a wonderful family!  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.
