animal.description:
Meet Bailey! 
2-3 year old female Shiba Inu/Doxie mix (that’s our best guess)
The sweet loving girl gets the worlds best mom award. She delivered 6 puppies back in September and was so devoted them. 
Sadly her family at the time was not as devoted and they dumped her and her 6 puppies at the shelter. 

Confused and hurt by this upheaval, Bailey found herself in a new foster home. A home that wanted to take care of her and her pups. Took a few days for Bailey to come around and understand that not all people are bad, not all people will abandon you!

Bailey is a love! She’s a lap dog, who likes to sleep under the covers with you. She’ll nuzzle her way under the blankets and warm you all night long. 
She’s great with other dogs, and cats!

Because of what Bailey has gone through, she is very nervous around strangers and new situations. With all the COVID precautions, we have not been able to work with her on socializing with new people as much as we would like to. 
She has visited the dog park and is slowly venturing out, but mainly just likes to stay right by your side. She had the chance to visit a family members house and she was visibly scared (shaking) at first, but thankfully she was able to start making herself feel like home after a short time. 

Bailey’s potential adopter will understand that she will need a little time to warm up to her new home, but we believe that due to her need and want for human affection, that won’t take long at all! 

All potential adopters are expected to complete an application and provide pictures of their yard, patio, and/or balcony making sure we can see the fence line and/or railing.  The application can be completed and submitted from our website - throwmeabonedogrescue.org - the link is found of the Adoption Process page.  Applications will be reviewed for approval before setting an appointment to come meet and possibly adopt the dog of interest.  In addition, those who live in a rental property are expected to provide proof that they are allowed to have a dog where they live.

Each of our rescued dogs has been de-wormed if necessary, de-flea'd (with topical treatment if old enough, and by medicated bath if too young), spayed/neutered, microchipped, is up to date on shots, and has been fully examined by a veterinarian.  In addition, each adopted dog comes with a starter baggie of the food it has been eating, a few treats for training purposes, a rawhide chew, a lead and collar, and a folder containing pertinent records.

animal.description:
Meet Savannah, a 1 yr old dalmatian or pointer mix female who was turned into the shelter in Coachella Valley, Riverside County, with her sister, Juno.  She is a friendly lively pup, LOVES to play with other dogs and is enjoying her daily walks.  She was shy when she first came to us but is loving all of the daily activity now. She has not had any training but is smart and can learn whatever is needed.  We are looking for experienced dog owners for this busy girl and a home with another young dog or two she can play and snuggle with.  She can go home with her sister, Juno, but if not, MUST go to a home with another young playful dog.  She is spayed, vaccinated and microchipped and is ready to go home anytime to the right home.

If you are interested in meeting Savannah, are not a novice dog owner and have another young dog or two, please contact Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc. by email to dalrescue@sbcglobal.net and request an adoption questionnaire.  You should also be able to access the questionnaire on line from our website homepage, www.dalrescuesocal.com.  Once the completed questionnaire is returned, and if it looks like Savannah might be a good fit for you and your family, arrangements can be quickly made for you all to come meet Savannah at the kennel where she lives.  She is loving life now but will surely blossom with a loving attentive family and another k9 buddy to play with.

To learn more about Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc., a 501c3 non profit charity, and to see all of our available dogs, please visit our website at www.dalrescuesocal.com.  You can also visit us on facebook at www.facebook.com/spottyfriends.  We love seeing posts and photos of life with your spotty friends so please, keep them coming.  Thanks!

Bailey Boo is a black lab mix who was born in late October 2020. She’s about 12 lbs currently and expected to be closer to 60 lbs when full grown. Bailey Boo is good with kids, cats and other dogs. She’s working on house training, basic commands and her puppy manners. 

Please note: as with most rescue puppies, we have no way to guarantee this puppy’s breed or size potential. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
Hi, I’m Mindy.  I am the happy and beautiful girl you have been looking for.  I’m a 1 1/2 years old brown Labrador mix, about 74 lbs of love and cuddles. I am super sweet who just loves attention and chasing a ball – sometimes I even bring it back LOL.  I love all people big and small and all my pup friends … oh, and car rides – I really love car rides. My foster mama says I’m super smart, know my manners (I know how to sit!), and walk well on leash.  Now that you know about me, the only other question is … how soon can you pick me up!

*All of The Right to Live dogs are fostered locally in San Antonio Texas and will be transported to other states to their new families upon adoption. We believe fostering dogs and not having them decompress in a kenneled environment is more beneficial for the dogs and builds their trust and companionship in a family situation. Adoption fee includes transportation costs, previous/current medical treatment (spay/neuter, etc.) and a health certificate for cross-state travel*

animal.description:
This sweet guy is Zorro. He enjoys going for walks and hanging out with his dog siblings at the shelter. He spent the first few months of his life without getting any love from people. He is a shy pup and because new sights and sounds can be scary, slow exposure to new things has been good for him. Zorro has taken a few car rides and done pretty well and he enjoys stops to eat a Hardees hamburger. Zorro appears to be a boxer mix and is a year old with a birth date of 11/12/19. He is neutered, up to date on shots, and healthy. Zorro needs a calm environment to build trust and gain confidence. We are looking for a home, possibly with a well-adjusted dog, that can work with him and help to expand his world.
***************************************************************************
This pet comes with an implanted 24 PetWatch microchip and free registration into the 24PetWatch pet recovery service. 
***************************************************************************
This dog is available for adoption at the Humane Society of McCormick County for an adoption fee. All of our dogs are indoor dogs with outdoor privileges. animal.description:
Ella is a gorgeous 7 year old girl who has come very far. She ended up at the shelter as an animal cruelty case. Ella was skin and bones, had pneumonia, parasites and many other health issues. Ella is very forgiving, no matter what she has been through she loves every human she meets. Ella is a dog reactive so she will do better in a home with no dogs and preferably someone with experience. Ella loves being next to humans. If you are looking for a dog to snuggle with please consider adopting Ella. This sweet girl is also great with kids and totally adores them. Ella has suffered a lot and she deserves a great family to love her forever. This beauty will do best in a home with a yard . We are sure she will make her family very happy.

Ella is located in Texas but can be transported out of state.

If interested in Ella please visit our website www.bravebullyrescue.org and fill out our adoption application

animal.description: Hey, I'm Kronk. You may be thinking, huh, that's a funny name, well I'm a funny guy!! I love doing whatever I can to make people smile and laugh. animal.description:
Meet Juno, a 1 yr old dalmatian or pointer mix female rescued with her sister, Savannah from the Coachella Valley Animal Shelter in Riverside County.  She is a friendly girl, active and loves to play with other dogs.  She has not had any training but is smart and can quickly learn whatever is needed. She was shy when she first came in but is enjoying her new 2 legged and 4 legged friends.  We are looking for a home with another young dog or two Juno can play and snuggle with.  She can go home with her sister but if not, a friendly playful dog in the home with her is a MUST.  She is a busy dog and should go home with experienced dog owners. Given her breed and age, she will need a fair amount of exercise daily to keep happy and healthy.  She is spayed, vaccinated and microchipped and ready to go home anytime to the right home and family.  Perhaps it will be your's.

If you are interested in meeting Juno, are not a novice dog owner and have another young dog or two, please contact Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc. by email at dalrescue@sbcglobal.net and request an adoption application.  You should also be able to access the application on line from our website homepage, www.dalrescuesocal.com.  Once we get back the completed application, and if it looks like Juno might be a good fit for you and your family, arrangements can be quickly made for you all to come with your other dog(s) to meet Juno at the kennel where she lives.  She is enjoying the constant playtime with her new k9 buddies but would surely blossom in a new home with a family to love.

To learn more about Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc., a 501c3 non-profit charity, please visit our website at www.dalrescuesocal.com.  You can also visit us on facebook at www.facebook.com/spottyfriends.  We love reading stories and seeing photos of life with your spotty friends so please, keep them coming.  Thanks!

animal.description: #710978Age: 6 yearsWeight: 50 lbs How this pet arrived:This pet was rescued by the Humane Law Enforcement Team on December 27, 2020. Why this pet is the one for you:Meet Wallace! Aren't those floppy ears just the cutest? Since Wallace came to us, we have seen that he is reluctant to walk on a leash, but LOVES food and treats and can be persuaded to keep going! Give this guy a dog-cookie or two and you'll have his attention. He also has quite the voice and makes a lot of grumbling and snorting noises, but have no fear, this seems to just be a quirk of his and not malicious in any way. Wallace enjoys getting scratches and attention, but he can get overly emotional and amped up. Wallace has a history of aroused and impulsive behaviors directed toward people, including jumping and mounting, but we have had success redirecting him with treats and appropriate behavior. His new owners will need to spend some time working with him in order to improve his manners. Wallace may be most successful in an adult only home, however, if there are kiddos, it is required that they be 8 years or older. If you have room in your family for this hunk, make a phone appointment today.	 Primary Color: White Secondary Color: Black Weight: 49.6lbs Age: 6yrs 1mths 0wks Animal has been Neutered

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. Copy and paste the link to access the sign-up genius for an appointment: https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet for dogs and https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1 for cats.

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time. 

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE:
http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Good with other dogs at shelter


Adoption Coordinator: Center staff
Location: Adoption Center

The adoption fee for this dog is $0. This fee INCLUDES spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description:
Hi, I’m Pepper and I just turned one year on January 9th.  I had a home and like so many dogs I lost  my home because my family didn’t train me when I was a puppy.   Puppy behaviors became less amusing to them as I became an adult but I didn’t know what I was even doing wrong. Ironically I know all the commands, sit, down, come.  I just get excited.  

So now I need a family that will  give me love and show me what behaviors they want from me.  Positive reinforcement works best with me. I’m a petite girl, my mom was a pure bred staffy bull and I weigh under 50 pounds. I love people and do well with other dogs but will only be placed as an opposite sex placement. 

 If you are looking for a beautiful, spirited, happy, smaller girl, I am the one!  If you want to meet me please fill out the application. I am a cross post for another rescue , but everyone loves me so much they are helping!


Pepper will only be placed into a forever home that is located within 1.5 hours of Lake & McHenry Counties in Illinois...(sorry, NO exceptions).**

If you are interested in adopting one of our dogs, please fill out an application:at www.aandsrescue.com/AdoptionApplication100109.doc

 Once your completed application is received, it will be reviewed, and then a volunteer will contact you. 

*We cannot do anything until we receive your completed application*

animal.description:
Meet Pennie, a 2 yr old dalmatian female turned into us by her family. She spent the first two years of her life outside during the day and locked in a cage at night.  So she's due for a fabulous home. She LOVES to play with other dogs and is the usual very very active and busy young dalmatian so she MUST go to a home with another young medium to large size dog or two she can play and snuggle with.  And given that she was bred to run 25-30 miles a day, she MUST have a TWICE DAILY STRENUOUS EXERCISE schedule to keep her happy and healthy. Walks around the block a few times once or twice a day just won't cut it with this busy girl.  Pennie would be best without young children.  We are looking for dog owners experienced  with the high energy dogs, dalmatians, cattledogs, aussies, border collies.  Prior dalmatian owners are preferred. Please do not apply if you do not have another dog or are not  experienced with the high energy dogs.  Pennie is spayed, vaccinated and microchipped and ready to go when the right home and family comes along.  Pehaps it will be your's.

If you are interested in meeting Pennie, have another dog or two and are an experienced dog owner, please contact Dalmatian Rescue of Southern  by email to dalrescue@sbcglobal.net and request an adoption questionnaire. 
 You should also be able to access the questionnaire from the website homepage at www.dalrescuesocal.com.  Once the completed questionnaire is returned, and if it looks like Pennie might be a good fit for you and your family and other dog(s), arrangements can be promptly made for you and your family and other dog(s) to come meet Pennie at the kennel where she lives and see how everyone gets along. She loves where she lives now but who wouldn't after the life she had before, but we know she will truly blossom in a home where she gets all of the love, exercise and attention she needs.     

To learn more about Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc., a 501c3 non-profit charity, please see our website at www.dalrescuesocal.com.  You can also visit us on facebook at www.facebook.com/spottyfriends.  We love seeing posts and photos of life with your spotty friends so please, keep them coming.  Thanks!

animal.description:
Serena D is a two month old puppy that will be joining AHR along with her siblings - Jenny, Blair and Chuck form our Louisiana partner shelter.  She weighs approximately 10lbs.  

Her southern foster Mom had this to say about her:

Ms. Personality, gives lots of the kisses, always playing with siblings or always down to chase and play with the bigger dogs.. has more energy than the other siblings but also settles down, when it's time to settle down wants to be next to another dog or cuddle up with her person.  


Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

FOR PUPPIES: PLEASE READ!!
Homes considering Puppies must be prepared for:
Flexible Schedules for Potty Training. Puppies can only hold urine for one hour per month of age. Crate Training for the next 10 months to keep them safe from chewing on everything in your home. Supervision with Children and Obedience training. 
Socialization; both with new people, children and other dogs outside of the home.
Homes that want a well behaved dog, must be prepared to put the time, effort and costs associated to train a puppy. Well behaved dogs are not born, they are trained!  Please do not apply for a puppy if you cannot or do not have the time for a puppy.

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

Lancelot will thrive in a quiet home where he is the only dog or with a neutral low energy large dog. In his previous home he bonded with one person more than the others-- so a single owner home maybe easier or experienced owners with fearful dogs. Please submit an application online.

animal.description:
MEET EVAN!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in it's possession. He is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4521195.

This amazing pup is currently At Risk for Euthanasia! If you are interested in saving this pet, please visit this site: https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/foster/BPAZ/Dog

Help! Foster needed or I will be put down 1/20 in shelter!

Hi I'm Evan, sadly, I am set to be euthanized Wedn., Jan. 20th, 8 am. One of the saddest reasons a dog can be E-listed is because they are mentally breaking down in their kennel. This is what's happened to me. I am really struggling and it is inhumane to keep me here in this condition....Can someone save my life?

Evan has been the perfect model for social distancing this past year, unfortunately for him in dogs its called "undersocialized." This means our big guy just isn't sure what to do with people or dogs near him. We're not sure what the past 2 years of this guys life has been like, but now he is wary of movement and hates his kennel. We don't blame him! The most heartbreaking of notes, "dog did not wag tail at all during interaction." Poor Evan just doesn't know what to do! He did have a positive interaction with a small dog, but never fully relaxed his skinny muscles. We recommend a very slow, calm transition so he can realize that you and your family don't mean him any hard! Evan is a handsome 2 year old pup looking for his furever home to give him a 2nd chance for the rest of his life.

To meet me, please call 480 331 4188 or message us here. If you have a dog you need to bring down for a dog intro. Dog Savers has got over 230 E-listed dogs in the last year out of the shelter alive! A small percent of the donations go to our operating costs to help these dogs get out alive. Lets keep working together to save lives!!

My ID is #A4521195...you'll need that if you want to save me. I am located in Phoenix Az.

animal.description:
Linus is a 10 year old Chiweenie. He gets along with other dogs, large and small, but he just really wants to follow his person around! He doesn't really like cats, and he hasn't been around small children. 

Linus has a cleft palate, but it doesn't affect his ability to eat. It just makes him look a little quirky! He also has anemia and a heart murmur, and he takes prescription medicine twice per day (if it is placed in his food bowl with his meals he will take the medicine with no problem). 

Linus is not 100% housebroken but almost! He does best when kept on a schedule. He will also use puppy pads. 

Linus loves squeaky toys!! He will occasionally chew on a chew bone. He also loves to cuddle and will just melt into you when he lays on your lap. He is a very sweet low energy boy who just wants to hang out with his person.

animal.description:
*********** RESCUE ONLY **********

CLYDE is "rescue only" which means that he will only be released to an approved rescue and not adopted out directly from the shelter.

CLYDE was brought to the shelter as a stray and was extremely fearful when he first arrived, so much so that his future was uncertain.  Two of the volunteers worked with him a lot and CLYDE is now becoming the dog he was meant to be!  CLYDE is still a bit timid when meeting new people and unsure in new situations, and considering how he was when he first came in, the shelter staff and the two volunteers who have worked with him think that it's best he go to a rescue organization first to gain a little more confidence before being adopted out to his new home.

CLYDE knows "sit" and "down" and he seems to be housebroken.  He has been fine with the other dogs, but no idea how he is with kids or cats. CLYDE is very food-motivated, so training should be a snap!  

There is no pull fee for 501c3 rescues and some transport help is available.



For more information about the dogs or the adoption process please visit our Facebook page and our website: 

https://www.facebook.com/woodcountydogshelter
http://www.co.wood.oh.us/dogshelter

Adoption Policy:

The adoption fee for any dog is $89.00.

Adopters will receive a $75.00 spay/neuter voucher. The voucher can be used for veterinary care only if the dog is already spayed or neutered.

Adopters will also receive a current Wood County Dog license.

The majority of the dogs available for adoption and transfer were found as strays, as a result the shelter does not have vaccination history. Vaccinations or vaccination history is not included unless otherwise indicated by shelter personnel.

State law requires the Wood County Dog Shelter to house dogs for specific time periods prior to the dog's adoption to the public or transfer to a rescue organization. All dogs at the shelter are available for adoption or transfer on or after their available date. Please call the shelter to determine a dog's available date. 

Adoption Requirements:

Adopters shall be eighteen years of age or older.

Adopters shall be permitted to own a dog at the address listed on the adoption application. Adopters residing with parents, renting their home or renting their land may be required to provide written, signed and dated permission by the homeowner, landowner or landlord authorizing the dog to reside at the residence.

Adopters shall not breed the dog and shall spay or neuter the dog, at their own expense, within thirty days of the adoption date or upon the dog reaching six months of age unless the spay or neuter is contraindicated in writing by a licensed veterinarian. The Wood County Dog Shelter may provide a spay or neuter certificate to the adopter in an amount determined by the Board of County Commissioners to reduce the adopter's spay or neuter expense.

Adopters shall provide adequate food, water, shelter and veterinary care to the dog in accordance with RC 959.

Adopters shall confine and license the dog in accordance with RC 955.

If you have any questions regarding available dogs or adoption in general please give us a call at 419-354-9242 or email us at wcdogshelter@co.wood.oh.us.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Fill out an Adoption Application
Puppy Adoption Policy:
To ensure proper house training and socialization, puppies will only be adopted to homes where an adult will not be away more than an hour per day, per month of age of the puppy, up to 6 months.
Puppies will be adopted out on a 'Foster to Adopt' basis. This means that if/when your application is approved to adopt, you sign a contract stating you are fostering the puppy until the time it is neutered/spayed at your expense. Giant breed puppies should not be spayed/neutered before 12 months of age. All non-giant breed puppies must be spayed/neutered by the age of 6 months, unless otherwise recommended by your veterinarian. We will amend the Foster-to-Adopt contract to make the puppy legally yours, only when we receive a spay/neuter certificate from you or your veterinarian. If the puppy is not spayed/neutered as required, we will take possession of the puppy once again.
Sandy is an English Mastiff pup approximately six months old. At some point in her short life her front left leg was amputated. She was taken in as a stray, so no one knows her history, but the leg is completely healed and does not give her any issues.
A dog carries 70% of their weight on their front legs so missing a front leg puts a lot of stress on the remaining leg. Sandy is a typical puppy that wants to run, play, and follow her owner but she also tires quickly. To compensate she will lay down often, if she's not moving she's laying down.
Sandy can navigate stairs, but potential adopters need to consider possible mobility issues as she ages. Outside steps may require a ramp at some point and it would be best if she doesn't have to navigate interior stairs everyday.
Likes: She loves touching. People or other dogs, it doesn't matter, she just loves everyone.
Dislikes: Haven't found anything
Personality: Typical puppy. She is friendly and outgoing. Playful and interested in everything
Temperament: Laidback. She's very calm and tolerant of anything done to her.
Energy level: The extra work required to get around tires Sandy out faster than a four-legged puppy would tire. She does enjoy going outside and playing but she also enjoys a good nap on the couch.
Favorite activities: Sandy really enjoys chew bones. She also enjoys attention from her human.
Good with: Sandy is great with people, dogs, and children. she is learning how to behave around cats.
Not good with: Haven't found anything
Housetrained: Sandy has never pooped in the house. She had a few accidents when she first arrived but after the first couple of weeks, with proper attention by the humans, she not had an accident since.
Crate trained: She goes in and sleeps well in her crate. She may occasionally bark but not for long and settles down quickly.
Challenges: Hopping on three legs is tiring and when tired Sandy can become unsteady in her footing. Carpets or secure rugs will improve her footing. Stairs should be kept to a minimum.
Any Medical issues? As she ages Sandy may need extra joint supplements. A good Veterinarian can help with her ongoing needs.
Sandy is a healthy, young pup that does not know she has a handicap. She will thrive in a home where she is loved and where her mobility needs are met. She would do well in a house with children or dogs and would be just as happy in a quiet house. Sandy is so sweet and loving, she will be a great dog for the luckily family that adopts her.
Sandy is being fostered in DeGraff, Ohio.
Application Fees, Adoption Donations and Rescue Policy: Please know that 100% of our funds are used for rescuing the dogs.
Our rescue policy requires the following:

Adopters must have their primary residence in one of the following states: Pennsylvania, Ohio, New Jersey, Delaware, Maryland, West Virginia, Virginia, and parts of North Carolina and parts of New York.
We will not adopt a giant breed dog to homes where the dog will have access to highly varnished hardwood steps inside the home. Any inside steps to which the dog(s) have access, must have carpeting, securely fixed stair treads, or a non-skid surface. We encourage you to remediate potential safety issues while your application is under review, prior to the home visit.
Methods or devices using pain or force on the dog to control the dog, or to deter undesirable behavior is prohibited.
Applications for giant breed dogs must be submitted by the property owner.
Homes with children under 6 years of age will not be approved for adoption.
Homes with children should have a fenced yard.
Pets currently in the applicant's home must have a history of appropriate veterinary care. Veterinary records will be checked.
All references must be checked before any visitation of the dog is permitted at the foster home.
All family members must be present during the home visit to the applicant's home.
Any dog(s) in the applicant's home must have an introductory meeting with the rescue dog being considered, before any adoption can be completed.
Homes with intact dogs will not be approved for adoption. Exceptions to this policy can be found on the Adoptable Dog Page.

For additional information please review our FAQs or contact mastiffstomutts@gmail.com
Mastiffs To Mutts Rescue reserves the right to approve or deny any adoption that occurs through this organization without disclosure. We reserve the right to make exceptions for special circumstances.

animal.description:
Applications now being accepted!! ROCKY is a handsome, friendly young lab mix dog who is estimated around 2 years old. He's come a long way in the last few weeks with leash training with his foster, but is still a work in progress. He is shy around new people (especially men) and takes a little time to get comfortable but once he does, he is the most loving dog.  He loves to snuggle and cuddle but also loves to play.  Rocky has never shown any signs of aggression with food, treats, or when he has been afraid of a loud noise or quick movement.  He is doing well with leash training and loves to go on walks.  His foster mom even takes him for long runs on a leash and he is the perfect running companion!  He does pull a bit on the leash on walks and is working on controlling his excitement to walk by his person rather than running ahead.  He has also learned to sit for a treat.  Rocky would do well with some obedience training as he aims to please.  He would do best in a home with another dog as he looks up to his foster brother for a playmate and companion.  
He's not yet cat-tested. Contact us for more details as we continue to get more information from our foster.

Adoption fee covers: all vetting to age (including deworming, deflea etc ), spay/neuter (to be done at 6-8 months of age if not already done and included in adoption fee),  free 30 days of pet insurance, 6 week obedience course (or reimbursement for positive-based classes), and lifetime support of rescue.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is FIFI.  What's your name? Anyway, nice to meet ya! I want to go home with you, wherever you live within driving distance to Houston, OK?  If you live close by, can you come to Houston to pick me up, please?
A nice person came along and took me in and, now, I am ready to hit the road to your house!  Uh, make that “our” house, OK?  I definitely need a house with a fenced-in yard cuz I need room to run and romp and be safe!  The rescue also requires an established vet history for a dog that you have now or have previously had.

Wanna know more about me? OK, here goes! I am a little Long-Haired Chihuahua/Terrier mix girl. I am 10 MONTHS old and I weigh 13 pounds. I have had all of my shots and have been spayed. YIKES! I am crate-trained and house-trained using a doggie door. 

I like other doggies! I like cuddling with my peeps. I like adults and children 12 and over.  Since I'm little, my foster peeps don't want me to be around small children. They might squeeze me too hard and I probably wouldn't like it.

I am all set to go live at your house. Uh, how about calling it “our” house, OK? Those funny-looking creatures, named humans, I think they are called, told me that they think that I am pretty darn cute. What do YOU think, huh?

Can you stand hearing more good stuff about me? I love people and I love cuddling......I get along with everyone and I am very affectionate. Just give me a few minutes, if that, and I will be your best friend forever! 

Oh, how I would love to have my own home and some peeps to cuddle with and they could love me and take good care of me. That is my first dream! My second dream is all about treats and playing and romping with my new family. Ah, I can see it all now!
If you would like to take me home (and you know you do), please email doggydarlings12@gmail.com  and she can get me on my way to a new and loving home!  My adoption fee is $350 USD and includes my vaccines, spaying,  and microchip.

Adoption fee covers: all vetting to age (including deworming, deflea etc ), spay/neuter (to be done at 6-8 months of age if not already done and included in adoption fee,  free 30 days of pet insurance, 6 week obedience course (or reimbursement for positive-based classes), and lifetime support of rescue.

Please fill out an application here for consideration: Tinyurl.Com/appshdr

* During this COVID-19 crisis, we are essentially doing only virtual application processing and meetings are using social distancing practices. We will not have any open hours until further notice and doing meet and greets by appointment with the utmost caution for personal safety. We are not a shelter so there are NO DOGS AT THE SHOP unless we have open hours. All our dogs are in foster care and are available to be seen by appointment.

NOTE: If a dog is listed as Adoptable, he or she is still available at that time. Also, our adoption area is within a several hour radius of us in Rochester, NY (NOT including Canada - sorry!)

animal.description:
Note: Dogs are pack animals and do not do well away from other members of their pack. The adopter is the alpha member of the pack, and the dog or puppy needs as much one-on-one contact with the alpha as possible. For this reason, all Route 66 Rescue Inc. dogs are adopted to inside homes only. They must be on leash, or inside a secure fence when outside, and not left outside alone when no one is home. Invisible fencing does not qualify as protection since other animals and strangers have access to the dog. The dogs must be returned to Route 66 Rescue, Inc. if ever given up by the adopter. Thank you for understanding we want only the best for the dogs you give a forever home.

Due to no fault of her own, this sweet girl is looking for a forever home.  She is good with other dogs and loves people.  She will make an excellent addition to an adult family with children over ten.  Her adoption fee is $200.
 
Please complete and return the adoption application to meet any of our adoptable dogs.
http://www.route66rescueinc.com/adoption-application.html Thank you for visiting our site. Please come back often.

animal.description:
Please only send inquires to the email in this bio all others will not be answered. Please read the bio before sending questions - we answer all we know about the dog here.

Chip is an adorable 5 week old pup who will be ready to go home at 8 weeks on Feb. 2, 2021 . This includes age appropriate shots, microchip and neuter. Get you application in quickly for this cutie

Chip's adoption fee is $400 - obedience training is required.

Obedience training is also required for all our pups. We understand with what is going on in the world that this may be a bit delayed. Please email us the completion certificate.

To apply to foster or adopt please fill out application at

www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

Thank you for completing the application. We are all volunteers and short on time, we will contact you back only if we have more questions or your application is approved and you will be invited to meet the dog. We apologize for not being able to answer everyone back.

For more information contact Kelly.V@HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

DOGS are in Foster Homes. There is NO shelter.

**Our companions MUST live in your home as part of your family.**We do not transport.

**See our website for more information. www.HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

All communication is thru email so please be patient with us. We are all volunteers and work full time jobs and have families of our own.

It takes anywhere between 3-7 days to process an application - the more complete the application the easier it is for us to process it. Please notify your vet that we will be contacting them and to release information to us.

ADOPTION PROCESS:

1. Complete this application
www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

***Everyone must submit an application - we only keep them on file for 1 month

2. Application background check, vet check, etc

3. Invitation thru email to meet the dog(s).

4. Adoption Contract

Meet Terrance, a one-year-old male American Pit Bull Terrier/Lab mix.

Terrance is a happy boy with lots of energy. He is exuberant and loves all people he meets. Terrance keeps a clean kennel and is very food motivated which should make basic training a breeze. We think this boy is so handsome, don't you?

Terrance will be available for adoption on 1/15/2021 at 2:58 PM.

If you are interested in adopting this pet please fill out an adoption questionnaire at www.yakimahumane.org. A Yakima Humane Society staff member will contact you once your questionnaire has been received.

If you would like to adopt this pet you can fill out an online adoption form at www.yakimahumane.org. Please give the name and ID number for the animal you wish to adopt.
If you are thinking about adding a pet to your family, be a hero, please consider adopting a shelter pet and if you already have pets – for life’s sake – spay and neuter. Spaying and neutering your pets is the single most important thing you can do to help decrease our nations severe pet overpopulation.
*NOTE: Nearly 90% of the animals that come into our shelter are abandoned, neglected, traumatized, injured, or ill. We attempt to give our best assessment of the animal’s welfare and temperament. Unfortunately, due to lack of funding, volunteers, and resources our physical and mental assessment of the animal is not always 100% correct.

animal.description: If interested in adopting a pet from our shelter you will need to fill out a request to adopt. There will be a overnight wait to get this approved. If approved, there is a $20 adoption fee for cats, and kittens. Adult dogs adoption fee is $75.00. Adoption fees for adult dogs at the shelter more than 2 weeks reduces to $25. Adoption fee for puppies or purebred dogs (no papers) is $100.  If not spayed or neutered, a deposit is required. The deposit is $130 for dogs and $55 for cats. Your deposit is returned after the animal is spayed/neutered. All animals adopted from the shelter MUST be spayed/neutered. Dogs arriving at the shelter receive DA2PP and Bordetella. Cats receive a vaccine for Rhinotracheitis-Calici-Panleukopenia-Chlamydia Psittaci. The animals at our shelter have been picked up stray. Please remember this when requesting additional information about the animals. Questions can be emailed to emporiakansasanimalshelter@gmail.com

animal.description:
Meet Missy 65#, 9month Lab/Pit Brindle beauty. She is an absolute love with all people she meets. She 

Missy  is a very strong, energetic girl who is going to need training, work on leash manners, and patient teacher as he is not house-trained. It is unknown what kind of life she and her brother had before a good citizen took them in after they had been abandoned so Missy is looking for a home with a strong, active family who have a securely fenced yard. It is unknown how she interacts with other dogs, but she does tend to be very vocal. While in foster she did not do well with the indoor cat. She is volunteer favorite and adores the kids. 

Missy says "Hello, people! I enjoy lots of cuddles; let's have snuggle time and play with toys too! Please understand I'm still just a really big puppy who is going to need training, including house-training, with my positive-reinforcement patient human(s). Please those with cats know that I really like chasing them and should probably not have them in my new home. I do love friends and look forward to meeting you."

Active Family Preferred

If you have further questions, emails are the only method of communication at this time. We all care about the health of our 2-legged caregivers and the community at large, so as a precaution we are temporarily suspending our public open hours. We are still taking email inquiries and applications, and will be in touch with you as soon as we are able. We appreciate everyone’s understanding during this difficult time! Stay Well!
.

animal.description:
Hello my name is Holly 
Please read my story because Ivy and I really need a miracle right now. Ivy and I was pulled from Caswell County Animal Shelter just over a week ago. Our owner dumped us at the shelter and said he had too many dogs .The shelter immediately reached out to our rescue because we needed out of the shelter since we were owner surrenders. The shelter was full and our lives was at risk. I am 3 years old and HW negative but Ivy is 5 years old and HW positive. My rescue said they could not pull one and not both of us so here we are. We have both been seen by the vet and and I’m in good health. Ivy developed a cough shortly after help came for us and we found out she has nasty heart worms! She is heart worm positive and we need to get her started on fast kill treatment ASAP. We must be fostered/adopted together because I looks to Ivy for guidance and reassurance since she I am a little timid and shy. We know we are asking a lot for someone to take on fostering or fostering to adopt both of us while Ivy is doing treatment but we know someone out there can help us. We are located in boarding now and Ivy needs a home to rest and recouperate in that isn’t stressful. She needs to remain calm during and after treatment and me be by her side and with her. Ivy has been started on doxycycline and will need to get her shots in 30 days so the clock is ticking for us. Please share in hopes to find us a foster home. Our rescue pays all vet bills and will pay for food etc if needed. We just need help so Ivy has the best chance of recovery. Please help us we are good girls and promise to be on our best behavior.
Love Holly

animal.description:
Zander is a neutered male Weimaraner/ Pointer mix born on 5/13/2020.
He weighs about 55 pounds and will grow some more. Zander is a playful and loving boy who enjoys fetch and tug of war. He likes to splash in water- play pool, friendly hose games or creek. He is a low-key, gentle soul who enjoys watching TV with his family (his favorite is Pup Academy on Netflix).
Zander has been sweetly social with the dogs (of various sizes and ages) and the people he has met. He has ignored horses in pasture at his foster home. He is very affectionate with his foster family, but can bark protectively when he sees new strangers. With an introduction, he has gotten along with new people very well. Zander is not suitable for a home with cats. He is very eager to please, highly trainable, and easily correctable with no more than a firm no.
This handsome fellow has some large scars from significant neglect. He was found at about 4 months of age with a deeply imbedded collar needing emergency surgery to remove. Zander should wear a harness, rather than a collar for this reason. He also has some other large scars which were healed at the time of his finding. Zander has healed well, both physically and emotionally. Now he just wants to be the loving, gentle puppy that he was meant to be.
He is house trained, leash trained, crate trained, and is intelligent. He thrives on gentle, consistent training and wants to be devoted to a family.
The adoption fee is $300.00 and includes medical care, deworming, microchip, vaccinations, flea and tick treatment, and neuter.
To adopt please go to the following link and fill out an application: https://www.leeshorerescue.com/apply.html

animal.description:
Meet Red Skelton, a five and a half-year-old male American Pit Bull Terrier mix.

Red Skelton is a happy boy weighing in at 70 pounds. He is strong and can pull on a leash so a harness might be best moving forward to help him with his leash manners. Red Skelton would do best in a home with no cats as he can't resist chasing them. He is outgoing and food motivated, sitting for treats on command; but watch your fingers, sometimes he isn't very gentle when a grabs them. Red Skelton is a great dude and he enjoys all life has to offer. He loves running around off leash and actually it doesn't take long for him to settle down, so he doesn't need a ton of exercise overall, just routine walks and maybe some backyard play with a tennis ball. Red Skelton loves to play with tennis balls, he isn't the most graceful, but gives it his all when attempting to catch/chase them.

If you are interested in adopting this pet please fill out an adoption questionnaire at www.yakimahumane.org. A Yakima Humane Society staff member will contact you once your questionnaire has been received.

If you would like to adopt this pet you can fill out an online adoption form at www.yakimahumane.org. Please give the name and ID number for the animal you wish to adopt.
If you are thinking about adding a pet to your family, be a hero, please consider adopting a shelter pet and if you already have pets – for life’s sake – spay and neuter. Spaying and neutering your pets is the single most important thing you can do to help decrease our nations severe pet overpopulation.
*NOTE: Nearly 90% of the animals that come into our shelter are abandoned, neglected, traumatized, injured, or ill. We attempt to give our best assessment of the animal’s welfare and temperament. Unfortunately, due to lack of funding, volunteers, and resources our physical and mental assessment of the animal is not always 100% correct.

animal.description:
Atchison’s sisters Topeka and Santa Fe have found forever homes and now Atchison is ready to find hers. She will need a quieter household, a friendly, calm, dog buddy, a family with patience willing to help this shy girl on her journey as she continues to develop confidence. A fenced yard is an absolute must. Atchison is completely housebroken. She is trained to use the bells. She sleeps through the night (not in a crate). Atchison is a quiet girl but will alert you to squirrels and approaching strangers. She loves going on walks. Atchison is treat motivated. She knows sit and is working on coming when called.

To be considered the first step is to apply here: https://www.pawsup4rescue.org/dog-cat-applicaiton 
Adopters must live within a 100-mile radius of Joliet, IL to be considered. The adoption fee is $425. This covers all shots, spay/neutering and microchip.

To be considered for this dog. Please fill out an application here: https://www.pawsup4rescue.org/dog-cat-applicaiton

Our adoption process typically takes from one to two weeks. When you find an animal you are interested in, we ask that you fill out an application as a first step so we can determine if your family is a good fit for the animal. If you are, then we will contact you to arrange a time for you and your family to meet the animal so you can decide if it is a good fit. If you currently have dogs, we require that the dogs be present at the meeting to make sure it's a good fit all around. Once compatibility is determined, we move on to the paperwork and finalizing the adoption. 

If the meet is not a good fit, we will keep your application on file for up to 1 year and we will gladly consider your family for another dog. 

Follow us on FACEBOOK: www.Facebook.com/PawsUp4Rescue/ 
and on INSTAGRAM: www.Instagram.com/Paws_Up_4_Rescue/

animal.description:
Google 'Austrian Pinscher' That is what he looks like - exactly. 2 yrs, 30 lbs. If whoever adopts him does the DNA we'll know for sure. Sometimes a dog that looks like an obscure purebred is actually a mix of 4-5 others. And sometimes it's the obscure purebred. Way back in the beginning, we worked so hard to save what we called a schnauzer/bassett - named her Snazzy. This was in Long Beach - 28 years ago. We were combing the soft cover Simon and Schuster dog breed book daily - and found a gorgeous purebred 'Petite Bassett Griffon Vendeen' pretty exotic name, eh? Turned out that's exactly what Snazzy was!
This guy will climb things.....and does not like to be left alone. Very gentle, EZ-going, friendly.
In order to get appointment, email your completed application. See beaglesandbuddies.com - adopt a dog section. Tell us all about any other dog/s, cat/s, kid/s - name, age, size, sex, spayed/neutered, how long dog would be home alone on any given day - now and after pandemic abates. Appts are 1 hr on Fri, Sat from 10 am to 2 pm and Sunday from 10 to noon. Tell us your 1st and 2nd choice day/time. Plan to bring entire family. We will email you - usually takes a week or so....
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
Sticks and stones may break your bones, but Stoney will only love you!  I'm Stoney and I am a 1.7 year old, lady lab/pit mix.  I weigh about 57lbs of sweetness.  I am a smartie who knows how to "sit" when asked, knows all about house training and the crate.  I am friends with other dogs and older, respectful children.  I do not want to live with any cats, so none of those in my forever home please.  I need a house with a fenced in yard (no apartments for this girl).  I am a pretty laid back sweet heart, but I need a confident, experienced leader who can make sure I stay on the straight and narrow.  I can be a little timid initially, but once I am comfortable, I'm all love and tail wags.  I am a girl who wears her heart on her sleeves and adores my people.  I am currently heartworm positive, so I will start treatment for those icky things and be ready in May to move in and steal your heart forever.  Fill out my adoption application today and I promise to always be your rock!

My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out*

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description:
This sweet girl is Philippa! She loves to run around and play outside! Philippa loves to cuddle and will come sit by your feet and wait for head pets. She is full of energy and loves to play with toys! Philippa is very shy when she first meets someone; however, she warms up pretty quickly and she loves to make new friends. Philippa does not get along with other dogs or cats so she will need to be the only animal in the house. She seems to know how to sit and it is possible she is house trained as well. Due to her energy level, Philippa needs to go to a home with no children under the age of 12 years old. Philippa is a 2 year old Pitbull mix and weighs 48 pounds. 

If you are interested in meeting this pet, please contact Chesterfield County Animal Services at (804) 748-1683, option "0", to schedule an appointment. Office staff are available by phone Monday-Friday 8:30 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. and Saturday 7:30 a.m. to 4:00 p.m. The shelter is located at 9300 Public Works Road, Chesterfield, VA 23832.

HERE IS THE ADDRESS: http://rescuedogvillage.com/forms/RDV/frm_adopt-rdv-cp.html EMAIL: IF YOU WISH TO EMIAL RDV YOU WILL NEED TO OPEN YOUR EMAIL ACCOUNT AND TYPE IN THE ADDRESS For more information about this dog, email: stormyvu@comcast.net PLEASE VISIT OUR WEBSITE RDV HAS LOTS OF PHOTOS LIVE LINKS TO THE APPLICATION AND AN EMAIL LINK FOR YOUR QUESTIONS. PLEASE NOTE EMAIL: you will need to open your email account and type in the address because live links have been removed by Petfinder APPLICATION: If this dog has stolen your heart, don't wait! Fill out an application https://www.rescuedogvillage.com/adoption-application/ to be considered as a potential forever home through our rescue. PLEASE NOTE APPLICATION: you will need to type the address in the address bar because live links have been removed by Petfinder NAME: Brady GENDER: Male AGE: DOB: 02-10-14 BREED Great Pyrenees & Karakachan Mix LOCATION: Terryville, CT DONATION: $455.00 WEIGHT: 49.4 lbs As Adult over 100 lbs Meet Brady, a beautiful Great Pyrenees/Karakachan Mix who just joined our wonderful southern foster along with his brother Ramsey. These brothers had quite a rough start, but foster mom says they are very quickly adapting to “the good life” and will be ready for their forever homes very soon! Their story is sadly a pretty common one. Irresponsible dog owners who do not take care of, nor care about their dogs enough to get them spayed. This owner’s female was purchased to watch his herd of goats and became pregnant. She had a litter of 8 puppies, and instead of finding them homes he decided to keep them locked in a cow trailer! They received no socialization with humans, no daylight, and no fresh air to run around and play in. This heartless man threw food into the dirty trailer for these pups, but as the weeks passed it became apparent that, due to their breed, they were going to be large dogs, and he knew he could not afford to feed them. Again, instead of trying to find them homes, he fed them less and less, until a kind neighbor began feeding them until he could get them help. It was only after the cruel owner confided in the neighbor that he planned to get someone to come over and “get rid of them” that the neighbor jumped into action. He found a rescue group willing to seize the puppies if the owner promised to spay the mother dog and this wonderful neighbor even offered to pay for it! It’s with the help of all the wonderful people out there that these precious pups are able to go on to live happy lives. Several rescue groups stepped up to each take two puppies, and we are delighted to have Brady and Ramsey! Every day they are learning more and more to just be happy puppies. These boys are gorgeous. They have luxurious golden white fur and sweet faces. They now enjoy very much running and playing in the sunshine, and getting lots of human interaction and affection. When choosing a breed that is right for your family, typical characteristics of that breed need to be considered. The Karakachen is an independent working dog, immensely loyal, and devoted to their masters, trying their best to protect their household at any cost. They have a strong smelling and hearing instinct that is instrumental in making them ideal guard dogs. Though not aggressive while guarding their livestock, these territorial dogs display a highly reserved nature while confronting strangers. Apart from their compatibility with children of the family with whom they are brought up, they will also be able to mingle with other smaller pets if socialized well socialized. Frequently described as “majestic,” Great Pyrenees are big, immensely strong mountain dogs standing as high as 32 inches at the shoulder and often tipping the scales at more than 100 pounds. These steadfast guardians usually exhibit a Zen-like calm, but they can quickly spring into action and move with grace and speed to meet a threat. The lush weatherproof coat is all white, or white with markings of beautiful shades of gray, tan, reddish-brown, or badger. They are smart, patient, and calm. The Great Pyrenees is an immensely powerful working dog bred to deter sheep-stealing wolves and other predators on snowy mountaintops. Pyrenees today are mellow companions and vigilant guardians of home and family. Brady is described by his foster to be a little shy and reserved. He projects a quiet assurance that he has all the answers to the world around him. He has a powerful, graceful stride, when he trots or runs; he seems to glide, with a little up-and-down movement. His gait is effortless and he is capable of trotting for 15 miles or more without tiring. Brady needs an experienced family, access to a large yard, long walks or runs and an active family that have owned or experience with dogs over 100 lbs. As an adult, his breed requires a confident, experienced owner, one who will gain his respect and understands his independent nature. Brady loves attention, is active and playful and will make a wonderful companion. He would do well in a house with a large yard and children they can run and play with. Brady and Ramsey have come so far and deserve a loving home where they are safe, have a warm bed, and are considered part of the family. Will you open your heart and home to Brady and Ramsey? ABOUT OUR RESCUE RESCUE DOG VILLAGE GUARDIAN, INC A 5513C NON-PROFIT ORGAINZATION WEBSITE: WWW.RESCUEDOGVILLAGE.COM We go the extra mile for every dog and do whatever it takes to make sure that that dog finds happiness, we give 100% and more. It is what we enjoy doing and helps us wake up in the morning; we know that the dog is thankful we rescued them and thankful for their life. Finally, they will be forever remembered by our families that adopted them because they really rescued them. These dogs deserve all of our attention, and in Rescue Dog Village Guardian, Inc A 5513c Non-Profit Organization, we are committed to our adopters and our dogs equally. We offer full disclosure and hope to make the best matches possible. Please know our adoption fees never cover our expenses. animal.description:
Fluffy is just the sweetest little girl and we are thrilled to have her in our care!! She came to us from another rescue organization after being adopted and returned to them (through no fault of anyone). Post-adoption, it was discovered that she is diabetic and requires insulin injections 2x daily. The adopter loved her dearly but was unable to commit to that lifetime medical care and it was in Fluffy's best interest to become available for adoption again. 
She is underweight right now, about 12 lbs, slowly putting on the pounds and she's feeling much better since starting her injections. We think that she is ~8 years old.
Due to diabetes and the requirement for insulin injections, Fluffy will need an adoptive family who has experience with this, as well as the financial capability to care for her. She is also on prescription food.
Fluffy has cataracts due to her diabetes and moves a bit slow but she sure loves belly rubs and is as sweet and loyal as they come. She is good with dogs and all people, super gentle and loving.

animal.description: Burton is a young, high-energy boy who is always up for a new adventure! About 99% of that energy is looking for love, rubs, and human touch. When he gets that, he is mush in your arms. This goofy boy was found as a stray with manners that are a work in progress. He loves everyone and will do whatever is needed to get your attention. Fortunately, he is also very eager to earn that love and get your approval. He knows that sitting, and walking nicely without jumping gets him a treat. He is a fast learner! Our wonderful volunteers have taught him sit, stay, and down; always with a handy treat! If you are looking for an athletic, smart, outgoing companion, Burton is your guy! He is looking for someone who will be patient, yet firm, in their training so that he can be all that he knows he can be to share his love in your home. Apply at orhspets.org.

animal.description: Archie is a 1 year old, 27 pound, strong, fun loving, energetic boy. He appears to be a mix of a cattle dog and corgi, he has a long body and short legs and bark loud enough to alert you of anything new or exciting. Because of his bark, apartment life would not be ideal for him. He was left at an EZ Mart in Oklahoma before being taken to a shelter and transported to Aheinz57, where he is now in a foster home. His early behaviors in the home suggest he may have been an outdoor dog. He loves the outside, but has discovered he likes indoor dog toys and has gotten used to the squeaker noises. He is mostly potty trained, but has had an occasional accident or marked his new territory. He would love a fenced in yard so he can spend time running, jumping, and rolling in snow outside. His human will need a strong grip on a leash as he has a very strong desire to chase any cars while out on walks. Archie really wants to play with other pets close to his size, a friendly dog companion would be ideal. His cattle dog traits show when he has tried to herd the small pets (dog and cat) in his foster home. They do not share his enthusiasm. If you are wanting a calm cuddly dog, Archie is NOT your match, but if you are wanting a fun, happy, adventurous, dog for outdoor activities, apply now for Archie. This sweet boy is ready to love you!
animal.name: Archie EZ

animal.description: Piper is looking for her forever home. She had a rough start in life. She was abandoned by her family when they moved away. She had 3 puppies in the shelter. When she arrived at her foster home she was very sick. She lost 2 of her pups from her illness. She is fearfully of strangers, so she needs a family with lots of patience. She does great in her foster home. She gets along with her foster family dogs and cats. She goes to door to let you know she needs to go potty. She would love a young large breed male dog to play with. For Piper to be successful she needs a low traffic home, no children living in the home, and a fenced in backyard. She is working on her fear of strangers with Pet Connection and they will continue to assist with training after adoption.

animal.description:
Kozzi is a Beagle mix who was born approximately June 2019. He came to us from Pulaski County after his owner was no longer able to care for him.  Kozzi is a friendly, happy guy who is keeping his spirits up and has been making lots of new friends.  And just look at that smile!  Kozzi would be a great walking or hiking companion, and also promises to always let you pick the Netflix shows - he'd just be happy to keep you company while you watch!  Kozzi weighs 34 lbs.  

Please note: Due to COVID-19, our visitation policy has changed. LIFE House is currently open by appointment only to individuals with approved applications. Please download the adoption from our website (www.lifehouse4animals.org, under the 'Adopt' section) and email it directly to the adoption counselor at amyc0405@yahoo.com. If your application is approved, the adoption counselor will facilitate an appointment for you to meet this animal.

We are located at 14 Fido Ct., Frankfort KY 40601.

If you have questions about this animal, please contact the adoption counselor directly at amyc0405@yahoo.com. We are staffed by volunteers and are typically unable to complete the adoption process on the same day that applications are submitted. Please understand that it can sometimes take 2-4 days to process an application.

animal.description: Rain is an young and active dog with a thirst for adventure! From chasing balls to running in the yard to hiking on your favorite trails, she is game for all of the above. Given her excitement level for new things we think she would do better in a home without small animals or children. Rain still needs to learn some basic manners about how to control the excitement level but she is quickly learning and responding well. She is very smart and eager to please. When she's winding down she'll just lean into you and roll over and if you sit down she'll sit on your lap. While we know she is a bit big to be a lap dog, she still wants a good cuddle now and then. Someone who understands husky behavior is preferred and would be the best fit for her.

animal.description:
What can we say about Iron Man, besides that he is EXCITED about EVERYTHING! He loves hugs, and kisses, and dewormer, and the smells outside, and toys, and chewies, and hearing that he is, in fact, a GOOD BOY! This dog has truly embraced all of life's gifts, and finds immense joy in each of them! We know Iron Man to be good with children 10+ but cannot imagine younger children would be a problem as he is a kind hearted young man. 
He has displayed some intense reactivity to other dogs when walked past kennels etc. and would prefer a single-dog home. But if you really have your heart set on adopting Iron Man, and you have another dog(s), we require that you bring them to your appointment for a structured and supervised meeting to see how they do together BEFORE the adoption!

The adoption fee is $250 and includes spay/neuter, first vaccinations, microchip with life-long free registration, deworming, negative heart worm test for dogs over 6 months. Age and breed are our best guess.

You can fill out an application on our website, newhoperescueinc.com by clicking on the animal's picture and then clicking on the adoption application button. Please read our COVID-19 and deposit policy on our website.

animal.description:
Someone to care Someone to share Lonely hours  And moments of despair To be loved to be loved Oh what a feeling To be loved Someone to kiss Someone to miss When you're away To hear from each day To be loved Oh what a feeling To be loved -from 'To Be Loved' by Berry Gordy Jr.                                                                                                                                                                      -from 'To Be Loved' by Berry Gordy Jr.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           Gordy is a 2 year old Lab mix weighing 55 lbs. This precious boy has a story with a heartbreaking beginning of total neglect. He is the oldest of over 20 dogs who were seized from an abhorrent breeding/hording situation where they were locked in a trailer with no AC in very hot humid south MS. His condition when rescued was deplorable. He was malnourished and most of his hair was missing due to non-contagious mange. To make matters even worse he had heartworms. This poor guy needed a lot of help and a lot of work to get him healthy again. Gordy received the medical treatment and nutrition he needed one step at a time to get him healthy again. He has his furry coat back, gained some weight, and was successfully treated for his heartworms. He has made amazing progress despite having never having any kind of training and little to no socialization. Gordy took to living the good life right away. His foster mom says he is a sweet goofy energetic boy who gets along with other dogs, cats, and kids. He is completely house trained and uses a doggie door. Gordy has done wonderful when taken to the local dog park and with meeting strangers. He absolutely loves toys, but he is still learning what actually toys that he can play with are and things that he is not supposed to chew up. Obviously he will need continued training and supervision until he has these boundaries figured out but this truly is the only thing his foster mom states is 'negative' about Gordy. He does have lots of Lab energy so he will do best with a family who will be committed to giving Gordy the exercise, adventure, and continued training to guide him to being the best boy he can be. Gordy is already neutered, up to date on all vaccinations, current on preventatives, and micro chipped. Gordy is eager to please and easy to love and he's looking for that family who give him a forever special place in their lives. No more moments of despair for this boy. Gordy is looking for his chance to be loved...what a feeling to be loved.

If interested in meeting this baby, you can find an online adoption application at     https://fjcasp.wufoo.com/forms/adoption-application/       Adoption fees covers spay/neuter, vaccinations, wormers and preventatives and range from $50-$125. All of our animals have been heart worm tested and are on monthly preventions. You can help save a life by fostering an animal from JCAS. If interested in fostering you can find an online foster application at    https://fjcasp.wufoo.com/forms/foster-application    If you would like to donate to help us help the foster parents with food, medications and preventatives you can paypal us at fjcasp@gmail.com or you can donate supplies at the LaundroMutt in Ocean Springs! WE ARE NOW 501(c)3, nonprofit and all of your donations are tax deductible!!
